title: Susan B. Anthony Papers: Daybook and Diaries, 1856-1906; Diaries; 1876

entries.fullText:
If this is found return to
Susan B. Anthony
No. 7 Madison Street
Rochester
U.S.
and a liberal reward will be given
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony offers a reward for the return of lost property.

entries.fullText: Rain. at brother J.M.s after two nights & one day’s constant rain - turned cold & snowing - - Their home never seemed so serene as now - letter from sister Mary - she thinks she is a little relieved from her rheumatism - but it is very serious still.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about the weather and receiving a letter from her sister Mary about her rheumatism.

entries.fullText: At Fort Scott - Pleasant as September - - wrote many letters to as many dower towns are then B. & M. A. A. Relative to lecturing - Heard Dolly play the piano & brother Merritt his violin & little Annie 17. months- just keeps the time with head hands & feet _ sweet as can be.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about writing letters and listening to music played by Dolly, brother Merritt, and little Annie.

entries.fullText: Rain. M. E. Church - Mr. H. Timberlake stopped Mrs Bloomfield_separated husband better drunken & shiftless_ left Fort Scott at S. P. now-weather soft & beautiful- Never had pleasanter visit with Merritt & Mary _
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about the weather and visiting with Merritt and Mary in Columbus, and mentions Mr. H. Timberlake and Mrs Bloomfield who separated from her husband.

entries.fullText:
( Mr. St John) Mrs. L. B. Thomas
Mrs. Catharine Smith - Farmer - 6 miles out -
Stopped at Steeles hotel - good audience
Left Columbus by stage at 6 A. M.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had a good audience in Carthage and stayed at Steele's hotel.

entries.cityOrState: Joplin - Mo. A. E. Gregory of Carthage
entries.fullText:
Mr. David & wife, Mrs. L. B.
Thomas drove me over to J. from C.
in P.M. - fine audience - Joplin
a mining town - lead - & very rough -
Dined at Mr. Gregory's before starting
for Joplin - met there Mr & Mrs St John &
another sister
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had a fine audience in Joplin and dined at Mr. Gregory's before starting for Joplin.

entries.fullText:
Left Joplin at 7 A. M. by stage to Oronogo
then cars to Springfield at 5 P.M - - to Cousin
James Anthony's - Had good
audience - week of Prayer - kept
many away - Mr. Shippley distressed at
by Social Purity lecture - but he is not above suspicion
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had a good audience in Springfield and Mr. Shippley was distressed by the Social Purity lecture.

entries.fullText:
The lady teacher who undertook
the lecture for $50 was taken ill - hence
no advertisement made - So spent the
day in Springfield - a two hour call at
Cousin Amelia Anthony Woseleys - (George)
- Party dinner at Cous. James - ex Congressman
Havens & wife, cousin Eliza's two brothers -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spent the day in Springfield and had a party dinner at Cousin James with ex Congressman Havens and others.

entries.fullText:
Left Springfield at 9:20 - at P.C. at 12:11
Stopped Decatur House - Mr Peterson -
Had small audience - This
close the week of prayer - which has
made me smaller audiences everywhere -
- Sent letters Slayton house Mrs. Stanton -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had a small audience in Pierce City and sent letters to Slayton house Mrs. Stanton.

entries.fullText:
Left P.C. at 2 P.M.
arrived Columbus at 8 -
Weather warm - so that no
fire was needed in morning - but
by noon it was cold & the
9 miles ride from Brownsville to
Columbus was wintry cold -
- In room with fire at 6.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Columbus and had a wintry cold ride from Brownsville.

entries.fullText:
left C. on freight train at 1.40 P.M,
Largest audience ever seen at Baxter -,
W. J. Lea. J & A. T. Lea. newspaper men
Capt N. D Ingraham. N. J. & McClure
Old Lady from Neutral- 83 -
came to my lecture -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left C. on freight train at 1.40 P.M, gave a lecture to the largest audience ever seen at Baxter, and was joined by several people including W. J. Lea, J & A. T. Lea, Capt N. D Ingraham, N. J. & McClure, and an old lady from Neutral- 83.

entries.fullText:
Left Baxter at 7.40 A.M. found
brother Merritt at Depot - no lecture at
Kansas City to night - nor at Fort Leavenworth tomorrow
So Stopped off - Letter from sister Mary of
Jan. 31st - Aarons 63d birthday - she
is no better - new doctor says it is nervous
debility -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Baxter and met her brother Merritt at the Depot. She received a letter from her sister Mary and learned that Aaron is celebrating his 63rd birthday, but her sister is not feeling better and a new doctor says it is nervous debility.

entries.fullText:
Fort Leavenworth-
Gen. R. & Mrs Saxton &
Mrs. S. mother Mrs Thompson-
no lecture -but dined with Gen. S brother D.R. & sister A[?]
left Fort Scott at 4 A.M. - brother
Merritt up at 3 - & May, splendid cup
of Coffee - reached L & found Car & [?]
& [sister?] B. at Depot -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony dined with Gen. S brother D.R. & sister A[?] at Fort Leavenworth and left Fort Scott at 4 A.M. to meet her brother Merritt, May, and sister B. at the Depot.

entries.fullText:
Oregon - Mo. Annie R. Irvine
[W.F. Drake]
Had splendid visit Mr. &
Mrs. Clarke Irvine - He had
a hand in slave Charlie Fisher
after brother Sam got him off [from Leavenworth?]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had a splendid visit with Mr. & Mrs. Clarke Irvine in Oregon - Mo. and learned that Mr. Irvine had a hand in slave Charlie Fisher after brother Sam got him off [from Leavenworth?].

entries.fullText:
Beaufort, Mo. - W.F. Drake
Principal Public Schools [Mrs Annie R Irvine]
The river up we drove six miles
is named 'Nishne Batue' when we
gather our [tobacco?] - splendid
audience - & had to get up
at 3 o clock & drive down
to Phelps on N.C. St. Fe & C R.Road
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony gave a lecture to a splendid audience in Beaufort, Mo. and had to get up at 3 o clock & drive down to Phelps on N.C. St. Fe & C R.Road.

entries.fullText:
Glenwood, Iowa - Breakfasted at
Pacific Junction - & drove
over to G. in [?Corning?]. E. L. Kelley
stopped - Mr. M. Henry Taft - Mrs
Nancy P- the wife - & Marcus H.
and Ollie - the children -
Splendid audience - Francis
Murphy - reformed drunkard -heard
speaking two night before -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony breakfasted at Pacific Junction and gave a lecture to a splendid audience in Glenwood, Iowa. She met several people including E. L. Kelley, Mr. M. Henry Taft, Mrs Nancy P-, Marcus H., Ollie, and Francis Murphy, a reformed drunkard who she heard speaking two nights before.

entries.fullText: Heard Francis Murphy's Temperance lecture in morning and evening – & attended Sunday School in P.M. – spoke at Sunday School – & at close of Murphy in eve'g – his stories made me feell as if dragged through Sibley of Andersonville & [neither?] refusing to seize key & unlock prison doors -
entries.summaryText: Attended Francis Murphy's Temperance lecture and spoke at Sunday School.

entries.fullText: Made 2nd lecture this eve for Woman & Temperance—
entries.summaryText: Gave a lecture on Woman & Temperance.

entries.fullText: Left Glenwood on 7 A.M. Mr & Mrs. Taft went Depot with me- arrived Clarinda noon – met Dr. VanSandts –pleasant--good people– Mrs. V's Mother is 87– 5 years older than our mother Found letters – forwarded by Ida
entries.summaryText: Traveled to Clarinda, met Dr. VanSandts and received forwarded letters.

entries.fullText: Stopped Dr–Van Santds– wifes name Ms Eliza H. Van Sandt Splendid audience– rode one mile to City in lumber wagon – Col W. P. Hepburn introduced me--
entries.summaryText: Gave a lecture in Clarinda and met Dr. VanSandts and Col W. P. Hepburn.

entries.fullText: [*sister H & Frank took 10 P.M. train from Rochester to Denver this eve'g [?]*] 2nd Lecture in Glenwood about half as large as first – but the very best people – & they organized a society- Ms Nettie Vance Hartford Pres – Mrs. Mollie Hepburn– Mrs Susan Barrett Myers- cousin of the E.A.C. poet [Mutice?] Myers – dined & slept. Col. Hepburn
entries.summaryText: Sister H and Frank left for Denver. Gave a lecture in Glenwood and met Ms Nettie Vance Hartford, Mrs. Mollie Hepburn, and Mrs Susan Barrett Myers.

entries.fullText: Left Col. Hepburn's at 8 A. M. son in law Thurnmel – Ada - in company– Found file of letters waiting at Creston – Ladies called Ms A. C. Rowell – Flora E Strough – M. C. Battey L. M. Bowman – C Robbins wrote 13 letters – Stop Commercial Sister Hannah & son Frank left for Denver 10 Oclock last night 20th
entries.summaryText: Received letters in Creston and wrote 13 letters. Sister Hannah and son Frank left for Denver.

entries.fullText:
Left Creston at 6:30 AM
on Freight--cold, sleeting, very icy.
Arrived at Bedford & at Bedford
Hotel at 10-- In P.M. Ms. N.
Goodsill called & I went home with her.
Found letters, brother says sister Hannah
& Frank expected there this day.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels from Creston to Bedford and stays with Ms. N. Goodsill. She receives letters from her brother about the arrival of her sister Hannah and Frank.

entries.fullText:
At Mrs. Napoleon Goosdsills--
very cold--Graham bread & oat meal
mush & splendid coffee. Mrs. G. a
granddaughter of the Hanford of our
Rochester Hanfords Landing--a
cultivated earnest woman--two
nice boys--
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends the day at Mrs. Napoleon Goosdsills' house in Bedford and meets Mrs. G., a granddaughter of the Hanford family from Rochester Hanfords Landing.

entries.fullText:
Bedford Iowa V. G. Halliday the P.M.
Mrs. N. Goodsill - Mr Hall & the
Temp. Ladies took lecture - good audience
- wrote letter to Wash. National W. S. Con.
the 27 & 28 - fear it is too late to reach
in time to be read.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a lecture with Mrs. N. Goodsill, Mr. Hall, and the Temp. Ladies in Bedford Iowa. She also writes a letter to the Washington National W. S. Con.

entries.fullText:
Hopkins - Mrs. Allan C. Kennedy
W. H. Blaley - Pastor Pres. Church -
Left B at 10 A.M. Freight - arrived
Hopkins hotel at 11 - Find letter from
sister Mary dated 22nd - first since Jan 9 heard
from home - also B & R.D. 1000 mile [?]
from brother D.R.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrives in Hopkins and receives a letter from her sister Mary, the first since January 9th. She also receives news from her brother D.R. about B and R.D. being 1000 miles away.

entries.fullText:
Left Hopkins at 2 P.M. and
Mrs Tillie Austin }Hopkins Mo
Mrs Jennie Frazer }
Mrs H. Morris (county)
Stopped to dinner & till 8 P.M.
at Mrs. Goodsills - then train to
Chariton at 1 A.M. & Bates House
Hellen Eliza - wife of Wm. Lloyd Garrison
aged 65 - died this day - Jan 26 1876
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony leaves Hopkins and stops for dinner at Mrs. Goodsills' house. She then takes a train to Chariton and stays at the Bates House. Hellen Eliza, the wife of Wm. Lloyd Garrison, dies on this day.

entries.fullText:
Garden Grove - Wm G. P. Arnold
Left Chariton at 9. found Miss
Miss Matilda Hindman on Car
she bound for Leon to night & I here
& she here tomorrow & I their
Another letter from sister Mary dated 23d [?]
Mrs. V. A. McNeil - daughter of Mrs. &
John R Cary - My dear Fathers 82 birthday
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrives in Garden Grove and meets with Wm G. P. Arnold. She also receives another letter from her sister Mary and hears about Mrs. V. A. McNeil's father's 82nd birthday.

entries.fullText:
Leon Iowa- W. F. Robinson Editor
Hotel - E.W. Haskett
Miss Hindmann here last night- good audience
Judge - Forey
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was in Leon Iowa and attended a suffrage meeting at Court House.

entries.fullText:
Sent sister Mary $100
attended suffrage meeting at Court
House - 2 P.M. & organized County
Society - Mrs. Wilson Pres - & Judge
Folrey Chair of Ex. Com - Train
left at 9 instead of 4.20 - reached
Chariton at 12 midnight
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony sent money to her sister and attended a suffrage meeting at Court House.

entries.fullText:
Chariton - Bates House
Miss Hindiman met me at Garden
Grove - Temperance Meeting in Hall
at 3 P.M. large audience -
Miss H left at midnight for east -
sat in my room & talked till late
- she is a woman of [?] of
common sense & easy speaker
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended a Temperance Meeting in Garden Grove with Miss Hindiman.

entries.fullText:
Albia Iowa Mrs. M. A. R. Cousins
& Mrs Dr. Phillips persevered in having
lecture though every Church in City
was running protracted meeting - here
small audience - Cold windy night -
Stopped at Col. Hurds -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony gave a lecture in Albia Iowa to a small audience.

entries.fullText:
Ottumwa - G. W. Bowen
P. G. Balingall - Mrs. Phillips
Jacob Millersack - old Ohio abolitionist
Terribly cold & windy -
small audience - Mr. Bowen
dreadfully disappointed
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony gave a lecture in Ottumwa to a small audience.

entries.fullText:
Agency City - Iowa G. G. Sampson teacher
A. L. Chamberlane (merchant)
J. W. Millersack - Mrs. M. Moeller the
wife of the Editor
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visited Agency City in Iowa.

entries.fullText:
' Trustee J. Hilton -
small audience - but good -
entries.summaryText: Small audience but good.

entries.fullText:
John F. Stephens - got up meeting - wants
Mrs Stanton Mrs. Anna S. Averill - teacher
Helen J. M. Cord - Mrs. Dr. Clarke -
Mrs Christian Slagle -
entries.summaryText: Meeting organized by John F. Stephens with several attendees including Mrs. Stanton and Mrs. Anna S. Averill.

entries.fullText:
Stopped at Mr Israels' - had fine
audience - but cut down by the Editor &
Hotel keeper - L. B. Fleak - reporting that
Mr. Israel me me only $25 & charged
50 cts admission to line his own pockets
entries.summaryText: Stopped at Mr. Israel's and had a fine audience, but was criticized by the editor and hotel keeper for allegedly charging admission to line his own pockets.

entries.fullText:
At Brighton - Lectured on
Temperance & woman in the
W. P. Church at evening service
[J Clark Coug]
entries.summaryText: Lectured on temperance and women at the W.P. Church in Brighton.

entries.fullText:
Washington H. A. Burrell
J. Clark Couger - his daughter
[Col?] Mrs. T. H. Stanton - stationed at Cheyenne - Wyoming
Miss Hattie Jackson - adopted daughter--
Mrs. Florence Couger Turing - Corning Iowa
Medora Couger - the unmarried one at home
entries.summaryText: Visited Washington and met with several people including J. Clark Couger and Mrs. T. H. Stanton who was stationed in Cheyenne, Wyoming.

entries.fullText:
Columbus Junction
R. H. Moore. Ed.
the Repub. Paper - opposed - did not call
Stopped at Hotel - at the Depot &
the 9th Sam'l Crocker - Ed. Herald - the
'Truly Democratic' introduce himself saying
next time you come - know your friends -
several earnest people but took no names
entries.summaryText: Visited Columbus Junction and met with R. H. Moore and Sam'l Crocker, who introduced himself as the editor of the 'Truly Democratic' Herald.

entries.fullText:
J.L. Brooke
Mrs. K. G. Holmes called - Fine
audience - though raining - & very
muddy - having fairly poured all last
night- Friends are numerous here -
& many in audience. - May W. Cogills
took revolution - Annie Buell Ross
lives here
entries.summaryText: Mrs. K. G. Holmes called - Fine audience - though raining - & very muddy - having fairly poured all last night- Friends are numerous here - & many in audience.

entries.fullText:
At West Liberty - Hotel
No lecture to night - lounging & resting
called an Annie Buel
Ross - formerly of Easton. [?]
wife - & at eve'g on Mrs. Dr. Holmes
& H.G. Holmes -
entries.summaryText: No lecture to night - lounging & resting called an Annie Buel Ross - formerly of Easton. [?] wife - & at eve'g on Mrs. Dr. Holmes & H.G. Holmes -

entries.fullText:
Left West Liberty at 9 A.M.
and reached Victor at noon
- got small & shabby room
at Depot Hotel - Mrs. Clapp -
Mrs Gridley & Mrs Tracy
called - & I went to tea at
Mrs Gridleys - none of them
for supper Mr & Mrs Colby
entries.summaryText: Left West Liberty at 9 A.M. and reached Victor at noon - got small & shabby room at Depot Hotel - Mrs. Clapp - Mrs Gridley & Mrs Tracy called - & I went to tea at Mrs Gridleys - none of them for supper Mr & Mrs Colby

entries.fullText:
Victor - P. B. Craven
The teachers of public school came.
Had small audience
and hardest work to speak
William S. Norton of Ladora
wife & daughter came over to hear
me. -11 mile waggon & 6 on cars
Mrs. M. M. Colby - Prin. Pub. School
entries.summaryText: The teachers of public school came. Had small audience and hardest work to speak William S. Norton of Ladora wife & daughter came over to hear me.

entries.fullText:
At Victor
Dined at 3 P.M.
at Mr & Mrs Colby's -
Spoke at eve in M. E.
Church to full house &
with freedom - & felt that good
work was done - many came
and expressed connexsion
entries.summaryText: Dined at 3 P.M. at Mr & Mrs Colby's - Spoke at eve in M. E. Church to full house & with freedom - & felt that good work was done - many came and expressed connexsion

entries.fullText:
Malcolm Mrs. E. A. Bates
M. F. Hurie
James H. Duffus
Left Victor at 11 AM & reached M. 12:30
Mr. Duffus parents Scotch -
weather very cold - night damp, roads
rough - protracted meeting- Small
audience - but good train - so
I enjoyed speaking - & they enjoyed too-
took 12.16 train into Des Moines
entries.summaryText: Left Victor at 11 AM & reached M. 12:30 Mr. Duffus parents Scotch - weather very cold - night damp, roads rough - protracted meeting- Small audience - but good train - so I enjoyed speaking - & they enjoyed too- took 12.16 train into Des Moines

entries.fullText: Took train at 12 midnight from Malcolm- found Mrs McKinney at Decorah at Grinnell going into Des Moines like myself to see & hear legislation went Toney house 3 A. M. - crowded. Miss Matilda Hindman addressed legislation at noon ---- I took the 11.30 night train back to Iowa City arriving at 5 A.M.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Decorah, Grinnell, and Des Moines to hear legislation and meets with Mrs. McKinney and Miss Matilda Hindman.

entries.fullText: Iowa City - J. J. Hamilton Prof. Currier called. Mrs Jessie Bowen Sterling also - and after I was in bed in Mrs. M.G. Hammond - an old pupil at No. 5 Rochester - Fine audience largely of the students -- girls & boys
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Iowa City and meets with J. J. Hamilton, Prof. Currier, Mrs. Jessie Bowen Sterling, and Mrs. M.G. Hammond.

entries.fullText: Mitchellville - Rev J.R. Suge Principal of the Seminary here ---- had good audience -- he has his 4th wife -- she is young & look borne down with care---
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Mitchellville and meets with Rev J.R. Suge.

entries.fullText: Indianola - Geo. W. Lee went in Des Moisnes on freight train in A.M. -- dined at Mrs M. A. Coggswell with Mrs McKinney, Miss Hindman, Mrs. work & Mrs Judge Miller - & took train for Ind. at 4 P.M. - had fine audience
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Indianola and meets with Geo. W. Lee, Mrs. McKinney, Miss Hindman, Mrs. Work, and Mrs. Judge Miller.

entries.fullText: Took train for Des Moines at 9 A.M. - Pres of the College - Burns - on train
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony takes a train to Des Moines and meets with the President of the College, Burns.

entries.fullText: A Des Moisnes - In evening Mr. & Mrs Tany[?] & self heard Rev King - Universalist on woman & the state
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends a Universalist sermon on woman and the state in Des Moines with Mr. and Mrs. Tany[?].

entries.fullText:
Des Moisnes -
Miss Gertie Dunn - agent
traveling for Gillette A. Ruller & Co.
34 & 26 South Water Street -
$2000 - & expenses - 10 months -
expenses - $1.700 -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony meets with Gertie Dunn, an agent traveling for Gillette A. Ruller & Co.

entries.fullText:
In Des Moisnes -
Mrs M. F. Gray Pitman
Des Moisnes -
Mrs N. R. Allen -
Maquoketa
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony meets with Mrs M. F. Gray Pitman and Mrs N. R. Allen.

entries.fullText:
Moore's Opera House -
- Bread & Ballot before legislature
- Complimentary tickets to all of them
& to the Clergy - most all went
& M Sunery says made a
good many votes for us in
the Legislature - but we
shall see
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends an event at Moore's Opera House and discusses the Bread & Ballot before the legislature.

entries.fullText:
Des Moisnes
Good notice in the
Register - sent copies to
friends - listened to debate
in Assembly on woman suffrage
- vote 54 to 40 - left on laid
awake on Mrs Saneys lounge until
2.20 A.M. then took sleeping Car
for
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony reads a good notice about her work in the Register and listens to a debate on woman suffrage in the Assembly.

entries.fullText:
Council Bluffs - good women no bad men
Finley Burke
Mr & Mrs Street - Mrs Douglas &
Mrs Everett - all connected -
had fine audience-
Mr C. D. B. Mills of Sryacuse
here - giving conversationals in
parlors
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attends an event in Council Bluffs and meets with Finley Burke, Mr & Mrs Street, Mrs Douglas, Mrs Everett, and Mr C. D. B. Mills.

entries.fullText:
Left C. B. on 5 oclock
street car for Omaha
found Julia Brown
Bemis glad enough to see
me - has two nice boys 3 1/2 & 1 1/4
Chatted over old Revolution days
& her Sister Elizabeth & Anna
Dickinson - Anna going on stage
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Omaha and meets with Julia Brown and Bemis, and discusses old Revolution days and Anna Dickinson's career.

entries.fullText:
Omaha - Mr L. W.
Kimball - Gen. [Nebet?] agt-
M.P.R.R. - Unitarian Church -
Mr Wm. Wallace - Omaha
National Bank -
Rev. M. E. Copeland
Lincoln - Neb -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her visit to Omaha and Lincoln on February 27, 1876.

entries.fullText:
Left Omaha -at 5 P.M.
for C. B - took a street
car ride with dear Julia
Brown - she is a splendid
wife & mother -
Mrs and Miss - Gen. Dodge
called at Mrs Bloomers to see me
before I returned from [Omaha?] -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her departure from Omaha and a street car ride with Julia Brown on February 28, 1876.

entries.fullText:
Council Bluffs-
Dohany Opera House -
- Bread & Ballot - 10 cts admission
Mrs. Dr. Osborne called -
worst night of season - snowed
fast- small audience- only
$8.80 -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her visit to Council Bluffs and the Bread & Ballot event on February 29, 1876.

entries.fullText:
Creston - Mrs A. C. Rowell
left C. B. at 6:40 - Mrs
Kate Cole - May Sutter's
cousin met me at Depot - & took me
home to dine with her and her Mother
then back to Commercial Hotel & to bed
- very cold & rough - small audience
still a good one -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her visit to Creston and meeting with Mrs. A. C. Rowell and Mrs. Kate Cole on March 1, 1876.

entries.fullText:
Marysville - Mo -
A. P. Morehouse
Mrs E. A. Edwards - spiritualist -
Central Hotel - left C. at 4 A.M.
dreadfully fagged - Splendid audience
- & one of my very best speeches -
bright moonlight night - and
warm again - Mrs Louise
[Vornater?] called -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her visit to Marysville and a speech she gave on March 2, 1876.

entries.fullText:
Savannah, Mo -
L. C. Stiles - Pres. Sen. Com -
Guest of the Mayor - W. W.
Caldwell - Left M. at 6 A.M.,
Large audience - Mr Stiles an old slave
holder - but C. an eastern man -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her visit to Savannah and a speech she gave on March 3, 1876.

entries.fullText:
Left Savannah at 8 A.M. -
reached Leavenworth at 11.
Sister Hannah met me at door
looking much better than last fall -
5 lbs heavier - - Sister Annie in
bed - been sick for a month - tampering
with herself - & was freed this A.M. What
ignorance & lack of self-government this
world is filled with.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrives in Leavenworth and visits her sisters Hannah and Annie, who has been sick for a month.

entries.fullText:
Left Leavenworth at 4:30 on
R.P. Train for Cameron.
Sister came down stairs to 3 P.M. dinner
Arthur called - Sister Hannah made
Custard for desert - Brother D.R. seems
anxious & overtaxed - O if he could only not
drive so much business & so hard - Dr. Sinks
examined H's lungs - not seriously diseased he [says?]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Cameron and has dinner with her sister Hannah and meets with Arthur, Brother D.R., and Dr. Sinks.

entries.fullText:
Chillicothe Mo. P. S. Funk
Dr. Wilcox
regular warm spring rain to day -
- at 7 P.M. cold & snowing
hard - small audience
200 - though - Mrs Col. S. B.
Taylor of Brookfield here-
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Chillicothe Mo. and attends a small audience of 200 people.

entries.fullText:
Left Chillicothe at 4 A.M.
arrived Cameron Junction &
breakfasted - & found my trunk
not sent - Leavenworth [11?].30 -
- Sister Annie better - but looks
very slim - she will rue the day
she forces nature - Hannah brighter
& better - but raises what shows
disease sure -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony leaves Chillicothe and arrives in Leavenworth where she visits her sisters Hannah and Annie.

entries.fullText:
Left - Leavenworth on the
4.30 R. P. train - wrote sister
Mary & mailed it on board -
- Sister Hannah going to start for
Denver next week - she feels very
much encouraged - gained 6 lbs -
in six weeks - arrived Allerton at
11.20 - & slept there - till 9 A. M. -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony leaves Leavenworth and writes a letter to her sister Mary. She also learns that her sister Hannah will be starting for Denver next week.

entries.fullText:
[Brooklyn] [Wm. M. McFarland]
Corydon - S. M. Miles
met me at Allerton - 5 miles -
roads fearfully muddy - stopped
at Mr W. W. Thomas - wife
Aunt Kate Thomas - daughter
Annie - only a village audience
but yet good -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony meets with Wm. M. McFarland and S. M. Miles in Allerton and attends a village audience.

entries.fullText:
Centreville - Joseph Goss
Court House - Key Stone
Hotel - Letter from sister
Mary - wrote Mary - sent interest
to her - which closes up Revolution
debt - - Good audience -
though very muddy - & raining all
the P.M. - but the admission
was 35 cts - [?] amount small
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her visit to Centreville, including a letter from her sister, writing to Mary, and a good audience despite the weather.

entries.fullText:
Keosauqua--Iowa
Russell Johnston
D.C. Beaman
Left Centreville at 12 midnight
for Eldon--Slept till 10--took
breakfast at 12 & train to summit & open
waggon to R. 4 miles--the very worst
of roads--Large audience in spite
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Keosauqua, Iowa, and describes the difficult journey and a large audience despite the bad roads.

entries.fullText:
At Keosauqua--stopping with
with Mrs. Jennette Strong--an old lady
of 74--her daughter--Elizabeth G.
Eno--next door--Mr. Edwin Manning
--Mrs. Manning & Mrs. Eno--the
two wide awake women--

Had packed audience in M. E. Church
this evening--Lectured on Temperance
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony stays in Keosauqua and describes the people she is staying with and a packed audience for her lecture on Temperance.

entries.fullText:
Left Keosauqua at 9 A.M.--the
cold very severe this A.M. & yesterday
--but bright sun in middle of day
moderated--rough ride to summit
waited Eldon 4 hours--

Reached Davenport--
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony leaves Keosauqua and travels to Davenport, experiencing cold weather and a rough ride.

entries.fullText:
DeWitt--
Rev M.H. Smith
Left D. at 9 A.M. and
reached DeWitt at 1 P.M.
Small audience--Letter
from sister Mary--Hannahs
house rented & all cleared
up--men & Louise--& [Eugene?]
were at home with Mary--
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrives in DeWitt and describes a small audience, a letter from her sister, and the people she is staying with.

entries.fullText:
Took train--at 8.50
for Chicago--arrived at 4 P.M.
found Mrs. Jones at home--
but Jennie at Vassar College--
a boy lover in the [fray?] & house too
Jack Grant--too bad--so
young as Jenny is--to get
entangled in love--
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Chicago and describes her arrival, the people she is staying with, and her concerns about a young woman getting involved in a romantic relationship.

entries.fullText:
At Mrs Jones all day -
terrible storm - lucky to be
in this pleasant harbor -
Friday A.M. (tomorrow)
sat for pictures at Mosher's
-wrote 20 letters to day -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends the day at Mrs. Jones during a storm and writes 20 letters while getting her picture taken at Mosher's.

entries.fullText:
Arthur Mosher's first
born to day - a boy of 9 lbs -
Wrote letters up to the
3 P.M - in all yesterday & today
mailed 40. offers to lecture in
Mo. - Took train Milwaukee
at 5 - landed at 8.20 - Stopped
at Mary Stout Roddis - 593 Milwaukee st.
found letter from Hannah of sister Annies
suffering
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony receives news of a new baby and writes letters while traveling to Milwaukee and staying at Mary Stout Roddis' house.

entries.fullText:
Waukesha, Wis.
L.K. [?] Neil
called on & lunched with Mrs
Eunice Gross - sister Annie's sister
a widow - May Stout went with
me to Waukesha - Harriet Stout
Hartwell lives there - Old times [?] -
- Had to get up at 4 Sunday A.M.
to get back to
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Waukesha and has lunch with Mrs. Eunice Gross, sister of Annie, and meets with old acquaintances.

geographicalLocations: Mrs. Marion V. Dudley--230 Martin St
entries.fullText:
Milwaukee--Wis--
E.A. Williams--No. 7--6th St
Mrs. Marion V. Dudley--230
Martin St--Liberal Christian Lady
Splendid audience--largest of the
season--though Stanton, Couzens,
Fred Douglas & Bayard Taylor preceded me
--Dined at Madam Annekes
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks to a large audience in Milwaukee and dines at Madam Annekes.

entries.fullText:
Left Milwaukee at 1 P.M.--
Dr. Ross Wolcott took me to her
home--thence I went to Eunice
Osborn Cross'--she is very
bright--but her future I feel
no certainty--lack of steadfast principle
--Called at Aunt A.E.D.'s all well--
then over to Mrs. Jones--710 Prairie Ave--
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony leaves Milwaukee and visits Dr. Ross Wolcott and Eunice Osborn Cross before returning to Aunt A.E.D.'s and Mrs. Jones' house.

entries.fullText:
9 acceptances already to my
40 offers--mailed the 16 & 17--
--got pictures at Moshers--not
satisfactory--but best I can get--
Took ten & spent evening at Aunt
A.E.D. & train at 10--P & F. Suge
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony receives 9 acceptances to her lecture offers and gets unsatisfactory pictures taken at Moshers before spending the evening at Aunt A.E.D.'s and taking a train at 10.

entries.fullText:
Robert P. Kennedy, Esq.
-Mr. O.S. Hutchinson, brother
of Mrs. H. Atillia Albro-Davidson
Austin - Minn - lives here & [?]
-Letters from sister Mary &
nephew, Frank - Arthur &
Mattie Mosher have a 9 lb boy born
on A.M. of St. Patrick's Day.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony receives letters from family and acquaintances.

entries.fullText:
Left B. at 7 A.M., failed to
connect at Forest - Staid over until 8 P.M.
-Mrs. Shafer, the Landlandy & Mrs.
E.V. Smith of Forest went down
to B. to hear my lecture--
-Mr. Jeffreys of Chicago Journal on train-
told of Jennie C. Clafflin taking him to her room.
Also of his New York sights - the fleas - an
obscene dinner--
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to give a lecture and hears stories from fellow travelers.

entries.fullText:
Reached Chicago at 6 A.M. -
Took breakfast & dinner at Uncle
Albert Dickinson's - Snowed hard - Went
to Mrs. Jones at 4 P.M. - Severe wind -
Lots of letters waiting - wrote 15 answers -
most terrible storm - no letter from home
or Leavenworth.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrives in Chicago and writes letters.

entries.fullText:
At Mrs. Jones - all day - warm -
snowing - slushy -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends the day at Mrs. Jones' house.

entries.fullText:
Bread & Ballot
Chicago , Ill Prime Course
Sky bright & day beautifully warm -
but the slush & mud deep - the Jones did
not go to lecture - An immense
audience - McCormick Hall packed
beyond anything this winter - & my speech
was easy & free & happy - & my audience quick
to see & appreciate
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony gives a speech to a large audience in Chicago.

entries.fullText:
Left Chicago on 4 P.M.
train for Elgin - stopped with
Mrs. Lois E. Hillis - music
teacher & independent thinker
letter from Sister Mary - it is a
hard load she has to carry - the house
& [?] - Mother & Aaron - & sister H's
two children Louse & Wendell - all this
beside her school & its boarders
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Elgin and receives a letter from her sister.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Lois Hillis
Had [H?] & Mrs Hillis & I went through
the Watch Factory- 500 employees -
Perfectfully wonderful in it’s perfections-
Then the Insane Asylum- Dr Kilbourne
Superintendent-very few at lecture-
most tremendous snow storm all day-
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits the Watch Factory and Insane Asylum in Elgin Ill with Mrs Lois Hillis and Dr Kilbourne.

entries.fullText:
Henry-Ill- Geo. Burt Jr-
Left Elgin at 4.50 A.M. reached Aunt A.E.D's
to breakfast 7.30 - R. I. Depot 9.45 - Mr Jones
there with telegram from Mr Burt saying
Lecture postponed on account of storm -
so returned with trunk to Aunt A.E.D.'s
Uncle Humphrey came in P.M. -
Staid all night -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony's lecture is postponed due to a storm and she returns to Aunt A.E.D.'s house in Henry-Ill with Henry, Geo. Burt Jr., Mr Jones, and Uncle Humphrey.

entries.fullText: At Aunt A. E. Dickinsons -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends the day at Aunt A. E. Dickinsons.

entries.fullText:
At Aunt A.E. Dickinsons
reading Mary Clemmer
Ames new novel - 'His
Two Wives' - pretty good on the
whole - but the same old idea
of womans sacrifice of herself body &
soul to an unfaithful man -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends the day at Aunt A.E. Dickinsons and reads 'His Two Wives' by Mary Clemmer Ames.

entries.fullText:
Ottawa, Ill - D.S. Ebersol
Clifton Hotel - Congregational Church
Mud very deep - so no farmer thinks of
driving in with wagon - small
audience - did not see Cousin
Ira's house - Too ill with rheumatism
to go out - & too far from to walk in the
rain & mud --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks at the Congregational Church in Ottawa, Ill and stays at the Clifton Hotel. She is unable to visit Cousin Ira's house due to illness and bad weather.

entries.fullText:
Left Ottawa on the 1.50
P.M. Sunday train - every 3rd Sunday
reached Iowa City at 9.30 - and
slept at St James Hotel - Then
took A.M. train to Ladora -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony leaves Ottawa, Ill and takes a train to Iowa City where she sleeps at the St James Hotel before taking a train to Ladora.

entries.fullText: Left Iowa City at 9.20 A.M.--found Mr. & Mrs. Norton at Depot waiting--live one mile north--the road perfectly dreadful--nice visit--Mr. Norton went down & carried the women to lecture--no sidewalks no crossing of streets without going over boot tops in the mud
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Ladora, Iowa and describes the dreadful road conditions and lack of sidewalks.

entries.fullText: Democratic Editor--severe storm came up just 7:30 which with the terrible mud cut off my audience--This week will cap all my later experiences for small audiences--but these towns are too small--
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks in Marengo, Iowa but a severe storm and terrible mud cut off her audience.

entries.fullText: --small audience--but better than the two previous nights--Had to leave at 3 o'clock A.M.--for Geneseo never lost myself in sleep before--& but heavy on sleeping car after--[?] took a good sleep in P M at Geneseo
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks to a small audience in Brooklyn, Iowa and then travels to Geneseo, Illinois.

entries.fullText: Wm. T. Allan--Pres of the Lane Seminary Anti Slavery Society--with Theodore Weld & H. B. Stanton--lives her & called--Splendid audience of City people--wholly--though roads are drying up very rapidly--weather bright sun and strong winds--A most cheerful letter from Sister Mary--of Louise Abil [?] Mary Dobbs with a storm [?] in her bed---
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks to a splendid audience of city people in Geneseo, Illinois and receives a cheerful letter from Sister Mary.

entries.fullText: Left Geneseo at 5.20--arrived Eldore at 1 P.M.--Dinner & good sleep--then at 6 good cup of coffee & piece of rare steak & rice --a pitiable audience--as to numbers--though weather is splendid & bright moon.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks to a pitiable audience in Eldore, Iowa but enjoys good food and rest.

entries.fullText: arrived at 5.30 P.M.--had good audience best of the fine little county towns of the week.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony speaks to a good audience in Alberton, Iowa, the best of the week's county towns.

entries.dateText:
Arrived Leavenworth Kan
at 10 A. M.
entries.fullText:
Arrived Leavenworth Kan
at 10 A. M. - found Sister America
guite herself again - brother Ian
looking better & seeming more cheery
Sister Hannah improved in flesh
but coughing more again. Then
last month of arden changes & some
of mud & fog has been trying.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Leavenworth Kan and met with her siblings.

entries.fullText:
Monday 10
Camereon Mo. C. N. Burnham
Staffed Combes House - E. J. Combs.
- splendid audience -
Splendid night, splendid
wheat fields all along line
of a no. from Leavenworth to Plattsburg.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Camereon Mo. and gave a speech at Combes House.

entries.dateText:
Tuesday 11
The A. L. train four hours
late
entries.fullText:
Tuesday 11
The A. L. train four hours
late - wrote letter & a - dinner
at Cornks House - took freight train
at 1:30 P.M. 7 returned Leavenworth at 6.
a tedious day of waiting -
Most terrific thunder storm
this night.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony experienced a delay in her train schedule and wrote a letter while waiting at Cornks House.

entries.dateText:
Wednesday, April 12, 1876.
Left Leavenworth on R.G. road at 11 A. M.
entries.fullText:
Wednesday, April 12, 1876.
Left Leavenworth on R.G. road at 11 A. M.
met Edwin R. Overall - Omaha-
on train - on way home from the
Nashville Colored Convention.
- At Block Station detained till 4 P.M.
- Rained & bridge open at 5 transferal
on planks lain over the track - got to
H-j at 8 P.M. - much of the track
under water.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Leavenworth and met Edwin R. Overall on the train. They were delayed at Block Station and had to transfer on planks over the track due to flooding.

entries.dateText:
Thursday 13
Quitman, Mo. - M. D. Skeels
entries.fullText:
Thursday 13
Quitman, Mo. - M. D. Skeels
Left pacific House at 5 A.M. for depot.
The rain poured - Q. is 15 miles west of
Maryville - Mud was almost impassable
before this flood - quite so now - So I
telegraphed Mr. Skeels & took train back to
Atchison where I waited 7 hours_then
down to Leavenworth at 3 P.M. - Painfully
tired out
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Quitman, Mo. and experienced difficult travel conditions due to flooding. She telegraphed Mr. Skeels and took a train back to Atchison where she waited for 7 hours before returning to Leavenworth.

entries.dateText:
Friday 14
Threw up this lectern to 17th to
enable me to fill Quitman.
entries.fullText:
Friday 14
Threw up this lectern to 17th to
enable me to fill Quitman. Straight
2 hours in miles out of Chillicothe -
- Went with Maud sister H. also she
hall out three teeth - Two of them permanent
teeth - been allowed to decay first filling
took chloroform - & acted just like her mother
over P. just to have each taken & krushed
& killed to within a ?? - took train at 7.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony prepared for her speech in Quitman and accompanied Maud and sister H. to have dental work done.

entries.fullText:
Sister Hannah left Leavenworth for Denver
this A. M.
Brookfield, Mo. - S. E. Taylor -
Reached B. at 11. last night. Stopped hotel
at 10. Mr. Elliot took me to Col
Taylors - his wife an English lady
Had small audience - not half
managed. Judge Torence & wife took
tea at Mrs. Taylors.
entries.summaryText: Sister Hannah left for Denver, small audience in Brookfield, visited Col Taylors and had tea with Judge Torence and his wife.

entries.fullText:
At Brookfield - Mrs. Taylors
went to church with Mrs. T. &
when to Judge Torences to dinner
- day beautiful & bright
walked both ways - full a mile -
Sister reached Denver at 4 P.M.
this day.
entries.summaryText: Went to church and had dinner with Mrs. Taylors and Judge Torences in Brookfield, Sister reached Denver at 4 P.M.

entries.fullText:
Laclede Mo. - W. A. Morton
& Mrs. Smith introduced me
- small audience - admission
put down to 35 - yet it didn't bring
a person more - the fact is only
intelligent will pay a dime, even, &
they will pay 50 cts just as quietly.
entries.summaryText: Small audience in Laclede Mo., admission put down to 35, only intelligent people will pay.

entries.fullText:
Macon Mo. - Jones & Brock
Took sleep & 5 O'clock Dinner
at Mr. Brocks. Had pretty
fair audience - Mr. Jones introduced
me. He & wife took me to
North Mo. Hotel - to sleep - as had to
take train at 5 A.M. - but didn't
till a 9 A.M. Freight train.
entries.summaryText: Pretty fair audience in Macon Mo., slept at Mr. Brocks and took a train at 9 A.M.

entries.fullText:
Kirksville Mo. - S. M. Pickerly
Rice's Hotel - Mr. & Mrs.
Miller - visited Normal school
Pres. Bowman - talked to students
300 & more - Letter from sister
Mary - Had to leave K. at
5:30 to get to Moberly & then left
M. at 3:30 A. M. to get to next point.
entries.summaryText: Visited Normal school in Kirksville Mo., talked to students, received a letter from sister Mary.

entries.fullText:
Moberly Mo - F. P. Prush S. C. Mason.
Mr. Mason is Pres't R. R. Literary Society
and Mr. Prush of the Dickens Club -
The latter society backed down & out of my lecture
- Mrs. Mason, Miss Wilson took me ride &
visit Car Shops of North Mo. R. R.
- Had splendid audience - Letter here from
Sister Hannah to D.R. & I sent it on to R.
entries.summaryText: Backed down from a lecture in Moberly Mo., visited Car Shops of North Mo. R. R., had a splendid audience.

entries.fullText:
- Left MOberly at 3:30 - breakfast at then
- Learn from Shellind to S. 8 miles.
- awful Juesh Hotel - after lecture
went to John P. & Matilda Duncans
their Son-in-law H. B. Tines - then out
W. S. man in town. Mr. Muhlon & wife
Emil, Manville. the Pris. Pack school
entries.summaryText: Traveling from MOberly to Shelbyville, visiting John P. & Matilda Duncans and other places.

entries.fullText:
- Left S. at 9:30 - dined Helbrina
& reached C. at 1 P.M.
Severe shower after lecture -
- took sleeping car to Cameron
but hardly lost myself -
strength & was so fazzed -
entries.summaryText: Traveling from Shelbyville to Clarence, experiencing a severe shower after lecture.

entries.fullText:
Got into Leavenworth on
time - 10 O'clock A. M. - brother
Jon & Nephew Houh Masher at tN.
Left at - took breakfast - read
up home letters - note from Sister H.
in Denver one week this P.M. - washed
& dressed - diner & took 4 P.M.,
train for Trenton.
entries.summaryText: Arriving in Leavenworth and meeting with Jon and Nephew Houh Masher.

entries.fullText:
Trenton Mo. W. B. Rogers -
stuffed with Mrs. Late
Herrick - wore short dress to
work in = =
entries.summaryText: Staying in Trenton with W. B. Rogers and Mrs. Late Herrick.

entries.fullText:
Princeton Mo. - David Speer
Henry Cadle - stopped at Mr.
Speers - good audience.
Left P. the A. M. of the 6th at
4 A.M. - got into Leavenworth at
11 - got bonnet - & Sister Anne & self
walked out to the Nephew Cartrans hazy
baly.
entries.summaryText: Visiting Princeton and stopping at Mr. Speers with a good audience.

entries.fullText:
Liberty Mo. - Geo. E. Patton
- a very moddest, refined young
man - 'Move the Dynasty, lost an
arm in the Last Cause' he wrote me -
No fresh word from Sister Hannah.
entries.summaryText: Visiting Liberty and meeting with Geo. E. Patton.

entries.fullText:
Ed, the Democrat paper got
up, the lecture - a wretched
failure -

Left Shelbina for
Loving at 12 midnight...
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about a lecture that was a failure and leaving Shelbina for Loving.

entries.fullText:
Stopped with Ms. J. F. Wright
had a fair audience -
and took train for
Chicago at 11 P.M. -
The Rev. Glendenny of Mo
Miss Pomeroy sellection [not?]
preaching here
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about stopping with Ms. J. F. Wright, having a fair audience, and taking a train to Chicago.

entries.fullText:
Evanston Ill Mrs E.C. Brown
& Ms Suggie B. Harbert
- Cousin Jennie went out
to E. with me - beautiful day
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about going to Evanston with Mrs E.C. Brown, Ms Suggie B. Harbert, and Cousin Jennie.

entries.fullText:
Chicago Ill - West Side
3rd Unitarian Church E.P. Powell
Had a tedious time getting down
from Evanston - no train -
Mr Brown sent us in Carnegie
to Grace Cemetery - & there [?]
& Street Band = Splendid audience
this evening - gave Citizenship lecture
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about attending a lecture at the 3rd Unitarian Church given by E.P. Powell and having a tedious time getting to Chicago from Evanston.

entries.fullText:
Geneva Ill - J.C. Robinson
- Took a good sleep in the
forenoon - Uncle Albert
went with me to Cars- found
Mr Robinson on board - stopped
with there = wife is Phila. Quaker
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about going to Geneva and staying with J.C. Robinson and his wife who is a Phila. Quaker.

entries.fullText:
Chicago Ill - Ill. State W. S.
association meeting in P.M.
small audience - Mrs. Mary Cook
Gardiner - Helen West Mead
No 5 Scholars - called at Aunt A.E's
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about attending a small audience meeting for the Illinois State W.S. association and visiting Aunt A.E.

entries.fullText:
Left Chicago at 9 A.M.
Uncle A. to Depot with me
Audience just 100--
so they were out expenses-
about $10- but I screwed up
my conscience to take the $50-
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Chicago and went to Warsaw Ind with P. B. Webber. She had an audience of just 100 people and received $50.

entries.cityOrState: Fort Wayne Ind Mary H. Williams
entries.fullText:
Mrs. W. met me at depot at 10 A.M.
it was here that I fainted on the
platform 3 years ago - from a cold
Hall & open scuttle door over my head
Mrs. [?inde?] to dinner & introduced me
Miss Nellie Hamilton Mrs. Wm sister
was with us - Mr. W. looking in ill health-
small audience - but Mrs. W would pay
me the $50- said it was her contribution
to the cause.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived at Fort Wayne Ind and met with Mary H. Williams. She had a small audience but received $50 from Mrs. W. as a contribution to the cause.

entries.fullText:
Beery's Hall. Pietro Cuneo
is Ed. Wyandotte Co. Republican
small audience - rained all
day & evening.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to Beery's Hall in Upper Sandusky and had a small audience due to the rain.

entries.fullText:
reached S. at [?] P.M.- at Crestline
bought ticket to N.Y. There ceased my
R.R. 1000 mile tickets-given me by brother
D.R. have used 3 R.S. 1 N.W. 1
C.D. & 2 nearly 1 Ford Wayne - &
1500 on Hannibal & H so [????]
Hiram Marvin - Mrs. Mary Madden
attended Ackron womans rights convention 1851 & 52
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony reached Shelby and bought a ticket to New York. She met with Hiram Marvin and Mrs. Mary Madden who attended the Akron woman's rights convention in 1851 and 1852.

entries.fullText:
arrived at 4.30 P.M. - found sister
Mary, neice Louise & nephew Wendell at
Depot--with bright welcome & an equally
warm one from mother at No. 7 - & then
Mary Dobbin Ditto - brother Aaron up
at Batavia - & Mary & Sarah & William
Hallowell called--to welcome me--
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived home in Rochester and was welcomed by her family and friends.

entries.fullText:
Saw brother A. only at
Dinner - very bland and sociable
it is such a pity- his delusion & snare
with any woman save his own wife dear Gula
can we ever get used to it so as not to
feel cut & hurt-
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had dinner with her brother Aaron and expressed her disappointment in his behavior towards women other than his wife Gula.

entries.fullText:
Left Rochester at 5:20 P.M. -
last night. arrived New York at 7 this
A. M. Found Mrs Gage at the
Lozier's all ready for work.
Mrs. Blake had [?] wedding
reception this eve. -I went with Mr. L
-rain forced - Mr. Gage had not go
-Merritt & Mary L's boy home this day -
Weighed 10 lbs -light hair, blue eyes.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in New York from Rochester and met with Mrs. Gage and Mrs. Lozier to work. She also attended a wedding reception.

entries.fullText:
National Woman Suffrage Associations
Masonic Hall -New York -
Small audience - and no work
systematized & ready -Mrs S. J.
Spencer the real helper -Very
efficient - & earnest - Julia
& Abby Smith present in P. M. -terrible
pouring rain in ev'g
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended the National Woman Suffrage Association meeting at the Masonic Hall in New York with a small audience and no work systematized. Mrs. S. J. Spencer was a real helper and Julia and Abby Smith were present in the afternoon.

entries.fullText:
New York state -W. S. Association
Masonic Hall New York -
Pleasant day -had audiences still small
all day -ev'g larger. But got
good reports in papers -the men
result of Convention.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended the New York state W. S. Association meeting at the Masonic Hall in New York with small audiences all day and larger in the evening. Good reports were received in the papers.

entries.fullText:
Rained all day - only Mrs
Blake came -Mrs Spencer Mrs. Gage, &
self -settled up Convention matters -
Took Train for Philadelphia at
3 P. M. found the dear Mrs
Thomson about as usual in health -& just
as cordial as ever.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony settled up Convention matters with Mrs. Blake, Mrs. Spencer, and Mrs. Gage due to the rain. She then took a train to Philadelphia and met with Mrs. Thomson.

entries.fullText:
Saturday A. M. I went first to see Mrs.
W. L. Webster - 705 Arch St. to see
her rooms for W. S. Headquarters
-Then Ms Davis & return. Made written contract
($100 per [?] -and returned to N. Y.
on the 5.20 train. Found Mrs. Gage
& Mrs Loziers -& all rejoiced with us
at the good success on rooms.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visited Mrs. W. L. Webster's rooms for W. S. Headquarters and made a written contract. She then returned to New York and found Mrs. Gage and Mrs. Loziers who rejoiced with her at the good success on rooms.

entries.fullText:
[28th Congregational Society Boston
Theodore Parkers old Society]
New York -heard O. D.
Frottingham. Then to dinner
with Mrs. Murray -who was so kind
to me in my Revolution days. Then back to
Mrs. Loziers & Mrs Gage went over my
lecture. Twin [?] [?] -& promised
Good-
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended the 28th Congregational Society in Boston and heard O. D. Frottingham in New York. She then had dinner with Mrs. Murray and went over her lecture with Mrs. Loziers and Mrs. Gage.

entries.fullText:
New York-went to Uniontown to
get A. P. native of Phila. Head Quarters
Mrs. Gage with me - & then to Francis
& Soutrel to thank them in person
for their great kindness in cancelling
my stationery debt of $900 - met most cordial
greeting - Mrs S. ordered Cen. W. S. A. Autograph
book - - - then to A. J. Johnsons - & he
made me Editor of W. S. department of his new
universal Encyclopedia -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to Uniontown to get A. P. native of Phila. Head Quarters. She thanked Francis & Soutrel in person for their great kindness in cancelling her stationery debt of $900. She was made Editor of W. S. department of A. J. Johnson's new universal Encyclopedia.

entries.fullText:
Left-
New York at 10 A.M.
Arrive - Boston - at 5.40 - found
dear Ellen Wright Jemison - at her
beautiful house - 32 Linwood street
Roxbury - all well - her niece Minnie
Osborn - & Maria's Aunt Carrie O. Allen visiting her
- Letters from E. M. Davis & Mrs Webster [?]
Mrs W. breaking contrat for C. Headquarters at Phila.
what will Mrs. Gage do to night when she leaves it-
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Boston and visited Ellen Wright Jemison at her beautiful house in Roxbury. She received letters from E. M. Davis and Mrs. Webster. Mrs. W. was breaking contract for C. Headquarters at Phila.

entries.fullText:
Chelsea, Mass- E.T. Strickland Jr
Mrs. M.M. Ricker of Dover- N.Hampshire
came for me- stopped at Mrs. Annie
E. Cheney's- 61 Hawthorne st.
Chelsea- Splendid audience & hearty
greeting from the people
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went to Chelsea, Mass and was picked up by E.T. Strickland Jr and Mrs. M.M. Ricker of Dover, N.Hampshire. She stopped at Mrs. Annie E. Cheney's and had a splendid audience and hearty greeting from the people.

entries.fullText:
Left Chelsea at 3 P.M.- in
pouring rain- Mrs Ricker
with me- returned to 32 Linwood
Roxbury- found dear Ella Wright
& her little ones all quiet-
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Chelsea with Mrs. Ricker and returned to 32 Linwood Roxbury where she found dear Ella Wright and her little ones all quiet.

entries.fullText:
At Roxbury- Frank Garrison
called in A.M.- tried to fix up
my lecture all day- at eve- Mrs. Allen
& Minnie & Wm. & Ellen & self to Globe
[?] to see A.E.D. play Crown of Thorns
-found P.P. there- It was a sad sight- the
public exhibition of paroxysnal [kiss?]
can never be made elernaty- no matter
who goes on the stage
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was at Roxbury and Frank Garrison called in the morning. She tried to fix up her lecture all day. In the evening, she went with Mrs. Allen, Minnie, Wm., and Ellen to Globe to see A.E.D. play Crown of Thorns. She found P.P. there and it was a sad sight. The public exhibition of paroxysmal [kiss?] can never be made eternity, no matter who goes on the stage.

entries.fullText:
At Roxbury Minnie & Mrs Allen left at 10-
M Garrison
called & visited a couple of hours-
Parker Pillsbury came to dinner-
Wm. Ellen P.P. & self drope to Sargents-
Jamacian Plains to see Azalias-
then to Cambridge to call on Nowells
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony was at Roxbury. Minnie and Mrs. Allen left at 10. M Garrison called and visited for a couple of hours. Parker Pillsbury came to dinner. Susan, Wm., Ellen, and P.P. dropped to Sargents, Jamacian Plains to see Azalias, then to Cambridge to call on Nowells.

entries.fullText: Boston - 28th Congregational (Theodore Parkers) Society - Hymns sung by choir (245) - 562 - 670 the two last -- splendid audience - terribly awed with my place - Mr Garrison. Mrs Parker was present & approved - Heard Wendell Phillips, Daniel O'Connell - in sermon Memorial Hall - at eving- Took tea at Mr Garrison- lovely chair darling Fanny presides for her mother
entries.summaryText: Susan attended a church service and heard Wendell Phillips and Daniel O'Connell speak. She also had tea with Mr. Garrison and his daughter Fanny.

entries.fullText: Called Mendums office- Jenny Collins- Boffins Bower & to 10 train- stopped off at Bridgeport over night with Rev. O. Brown ( Willis )- nice boy baby- lost her Parish- but bright & hopeful- good husband
entries.summaryText: Susan made some stops and stayed overnight in Bridgeport with Rev. O. Brown and his family.

entries.fullText: Left Olympia Brown home at 11 A.M. - Lunched Mrs. Blake- called on Mrs. Phillips- & Mrs. Lozier- and reached Phila- Mrs. Thomsons at 7 P.m. - found Mrs Gage there also their friends James Purrington, wife, son & daughter of Lyons, Mass-
entries.summaryText: Susan traveled to Philadelphia and visited with various friends and acquaintances.

entries.fullText: In Phila- Spent day in meeting rooms- in P.M. attended Radical Club at 333 Walnit St.- Mr Davis absent- Mister Copper minus met Judge Westbrook - & with him fixed upon 1431 Chestnut as rooms- Letter from Letter Mary- fear [?] Hannah is not improving - & [?] that she must be losing-
entries.summaryText: Susan attended a meeting and a Radical Club event in Philadelphia. She also received a letter from her sister Mary about their sister Hannah's health.

entries.fullText: 1431 Chestnut St.- Phila. Pa National Woman Suffrage Parlors- slept in them for the first time this night- Wrote Sister Mary- Mr & Mrs Judge Westbrook called-
entries.summaryText: Susan stayed at the National Woman Suffrage Parlors in Philadelphia and received a visit from Judge Westbrook and his wife.

entries.fullText: Dear Lucretia Mott called at 2 P.M. - really our first call- so her name must go first into Centennial Autograph Book- went with her to see the English Gentleman- Wilson & Gladstone on Legislation on Society evil.
entries.summaryText: Susan visited with Lucretia Mott and went to see an English Gentleman speak about legislation on society's problems.

entries.fullText:
Messrs Wilson, Gladstone at 11 -
Only Mr Wilson called - gave
account of English Laws for
licensing & registering Prostitution
- most demoralizing - going to New
York & Boston - & then return here
June 12th - Mr G. & self went to
Musical Fund Hall to meeting to open
exposition Sunday
entries.summaryText: Meeting with Wilson and Gladstone, discussed English laws for licensing and registering prostitution. Going to New York and Boston.

entries.fullText:
- Did not go to Church - wrote
& felt unsettled all day - at
eve - Mrs G. & self called on
the Purvis' - Robert in Washington
the daughters - Hattie & Georgie
at home - both feeble -
entries.summaryText: Did not go to church, felt unsettled. Visited the Purvis' and saw Hattie and Georgie who were both feeble.

entries.fullText:
all these days spent in getting
Parlors in order - & paper & circulars
printed - such a crowd of
work to be done for every body -
but it is slow getting on -
entries.summaryText: Spent the last few days getting parlors in order and printing paper and circulars. Slow progress.

entries.fullText:
Lucretia Mott & Sarah
Pugh called - & in P.M.
Hattie Purvis - & she told me of
her & her father experience with A. E. D.
and her sister Sue -
entries.summaryText: Lucretia Mott and Sarah Pugh visited. Hattie Purvis shared her and her father's experience with A. E. D. and her sister Sue.

entries.fullText:
Reception at National W. S. Parlors
for Liberal Club & Citizen Suffrage society
of Phila - a very pleasant company -
day very warm - dropped off all flannels this
P.M -
entries.summaryText: Attended a reception for Liberal Club and Citizen Suffrage society of Phila. Dropped off all flannels in the afternoon.

entries.fullText:
At Breakfast at West End - Sarah
Hurn called -
entries.summaryText: Had breakfast at West End. Sarah Hurn called.

entries.fullText:
Next to Exhibition
grounds to the 76 Club
dinner - they had wine
& simply did as men
have always done - drank
c& toasted
entries.summaryText: Attended 76 Club dinner at Exhibition grounds. They had wine and toasted.

entries.fullText:
76 Press Club reception - a
very good representation
entries.summaryText: Attended 76 Press Club reception with good representation.

entries.fullText:
Went to hear Ms
Welling preach - very
common place - but the
face of a woman in that
pulpit was grand
entries.summaryText: Attended a sermon by Ms. Welling and was moved by seeing a woman in the pulpit.

entries.fullText:
Ms Sargent & Ella & Lizzie
& Georgie came
entries.summaryText: Visited by Ms. Sargent, Ella, Lizzie, and Georgie.

entries.fullText:
Called on G. W. Child -
gave me $100 - for our work -
had pleasant call on Mrs
Forney - had meeting for Wilson
on C. D. Arts of England - Medical
Women of city present - Lucretia
Mott present
entries.summaryText: Received $100 from G. W. Child for their work, had a pleasant visit with Mrs. Forney, attended a meeting on C. D. Arts of England with Medical Women of the city and Lucretia Mott.

entries.fullText:
Mrs. Stevenson left - went depot
[?] had pocket book stolen from
dress pocket - $8. It was the one given
me birth day - 1870. by Lucretia Mott-
done most adroitly - spent the day going
to Editorial offices. Very pleasant receptions -
went to [?????el] Club
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Stevenson left, pocket book stolen, went to editorial offices and club.

entries.fullText:
Mrs. Stanton arrived this A.M.
Glad enough to see her & to feel her
strength come in - went to Temperance
Breakfast - gave notice of W. T.
rooms & receptions this eve - to Mrs.
Sargent & Phebe Couzens -
Large number at reception-
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Stanton arrived, went to temperance breakfast and gave notice of W.T. rooms and receptions.

entries.fullText:
- The Repub. Con. platform views
with pleasure & promise respectful condition
agree to women -
entries.summaryText: Republican Convention platform views on women.

entries.fullText:
Mrs. S & Gage - wrote on
Dem. Address all day-
I went to tea to Helen
E. Potters - the elocutionist -
- Miss R. H. Cleff of Nevada
there - Phebe Couzins & others- she
set wine before her guests-
I protested -
entries.summaryText: Mrs. S and Gage wrote on Democratic Address, went to tea with Helen E. Potters, protested against wine being served.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Sargents, Gage. Stanton
& self took breakfast & dinner together
at West End Hotel - Mrs. S. &
all the children are remarkable
for sincerity, transparency -
-at eve - I called at Dr. B.
Longshore's -
entries.summaryText: Had breakfast and dinner with Mrs. Sargents, Gage, and Stanton. Called at Dr. B. Longshore's in the evening.

entries.fullText:
Spent whole A.M. to 12:30
going to Printing offices &c- called
on Mrs. Forney - great chagrin
at the nomination of Hayes & Wheeler
The Sargents left this noon -
Giles & C.F. Stebbins called - Phebe
Couzins left- St. Louis to - Dem. Con -
Ada Thomson got ticket of Tom Scott
entries.summaryText: Went to printing offices, called on Mrs. Forney, Sargents left, Phebe Couzins left for St. Louis Democratic Convention.

entries.fullText:
Had splendid nights sleep,
at Miss Thomson- 114 North 11th -
- had slept on sofa here at Parlors
the four nights before last - almost
no real rest- so was ready put in sound sleep
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had a good night's sleep at Miss Thomson's place after several nights of poor rest on a sofa at the Parlors.

entries.fullText:
Dinner at 5 P.M. Miss Helen
E. Potters - 2308 St. Alban's Place.
Pleasant visit - Miss
Potter going to personate
Mrs. Stanton & Anthony
in her entertainment
the coming winter -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had dinner with Miss Helen E. Potters and discussed her upcoming performance where she will portray Mrs. Stanton and Anthony.

entries.fullText:
a reception at Parlors
very hot indeed-
Mrs. Sara J. Spencer
came this A.M. and set
about putting her idea
of Declaration & protest
on paper-
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony attended a reception at the Parlors where Mrs. Sara J. Spencer discussed her idea for a Declaration and protest.

entries.fullText:
Mrs. Spencer took
both Stanton & Gages Declaration
& wrote hers from them -
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Spencer used both Stanton and Gages Declaration to write her own.

entries.fullText:
Dreadfully hot -
worked all day - Mrs. S & G.
too - sending off Dem. address
& on the Declaration & protest
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony and Mrs. S & G worked on sending off a Democratic address and the Declaration and protest on a hot day.

entries.fullText:
Very Hot - slept at Miss [Thomans?]
- letter from Mary L. & Merritt. Their
baby boy home May 9th with light
hair & blue eyes -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about the weather and receiving a letter from Mary L. and Merritt about their baby boy.

entries.fullText:
Democratic Con.
at St Louis - Our
delegate Mrs P. W. Couzins
got a hearing
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about the Democratic Convention in St. Louis and how their delegate, Mrs. P. W. Couzins, got a hearing.

entries.fullText:
Work; all day
Stanton - Anthony, Gage -
getting off Declarations, -
Mrs. Spencer writing-
engrossing new Declaration -
Phoebe Couzins returned
from St.Louis this A.M. -
entries.summaryText: Worked all day. Stanton, Anthony, Gage, Mrs. Spencer, and Phoebe Couzins were getting off Declarations and engrossing new Declaration. Phoebe Couzins returned from St.Louis.

entries.fullText:
Mrs. Gage, Mrs. Couzins, Mrs. Blake
& Mrs. Spencer & self - took seats
on platform Independence Square -
& I presented woman's Declaration of Rights
to Vice Pres. Ferry -
entries.summaryText: Took seats on platform Independence Square and presented woman's Declaration of Rights to Vice Pres. Ferry. Mrs. Gage, Mrs. Couzins, Mrs. Blake, Mrs. Spencer, and self were present.

entries.fullText:
Mrs. Stanton left for home
this P.M-
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Stanton left for home in the afternoon.

entries.fullText:
Large numbers at reception
- Robert Purvis spoke with old
fire - Phoebe Couzins outdid
herself -
entries.summaryText: Large numbers at reception. Robert Purvis spoke with old fire and Phoebe Couzins outdid herself.

entries.fullText:
Mrs. Gages daughter
Helen left - Universal
Peace Con. began this A.M
- went down with Lucretia
Mott -
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Gages daughter Helen left for Universal. Peace Convention began and went down with Lucretia Mott.

entries.fullText:
[?] -
few called - Mrs M. [?].
Longley of Ohio - but
would not sign Declaration
because she was member
of American Society -
Maud & Julia Gage
left this A.M -
entries.summaryText: Few people called. Longley of Ohio would not sign Declaration because she was a member of American Society. Maud and Julia Gage left this morning.

entries.fullText: Mrs. Gage left for her house- has been here two weeks - next to Peace meeting- -Freedom of speech to Senators ruins the principle in the grand- reception- pleasant- not very large- dreadfully hot- Phebe Hanaford Willis- also J.C. Wildman of the [? doster] class-
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Gage left for her house after being here for two weeks. Attended a Peace meeting and discussed the Freedom of speech to Senators. Pleasant reception but dreadfully hot. Phebe Hanaford Willis and J.C. Wildman were also present.

entries.fullText: Received the Parchment Declaration from Mrs. Sargent.
entries.summaryText: Received the Parchment Declaration from Mrs. Sargent.

entries.fullText: [Mrs. Gage's Helen left this morn-]
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Gage's Helen left this morning.

entries.fullText: This is for July 11th [Hard shower - kept out [?] people from calling Mrs M [?] Longly called but would not put her name to Declaration - because she belonged to American [?] spirit - Mrs Gage Julie & Maud left this A.M.]
entries.summaryText: Mrs. M Longly called but would not put her name to Declaration because she belonged to American spirit. Mrs. Gage, Julie, and Maud left this morning.

entries.fullText: Had goodly numbers last evening - large meeting at 333 Walnut St.- this P.M. Mrs Stanton, Mrs Rosebud gave letters
entries.summaryText: Large meeting at 333 Walnut St. Mrs. Stanton and Mrs. Rosebud gave letters.

entries.fullText:
Reception from 10 to 1/2 past 1-
in honor of Lucretia Mott-
- She & I stated cause of
Lucy Stone's dividing our Society -
- Mrs. Child, Mrs Hindman
said very fairly -
Slept at Miss Thompsons
James went over with me heavy [shower?] -
entries.summaryText: Reception in honor of Lucretia Mott, discussed Lucy Stone's dividing the Society, stayed at Miss Thompsons.

entries.fullText:
Left Phila at 8.30 -
the rain had cooled the air -
reached Tenafly at 5 P.M-
tired tired —
entries.summaryText: Left Phila for Tenafly, tired.

entries.fullText:
Cousin Fannie Dickinson
at Rochester - on way to Phila -
entries.summaryText: Cousin Fannie Dickinson in Rochester on way to Phila.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Blake came out
to lunch - also Mr -
Newhold- newspaper reporter
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Blake and Mr. Newhold, a newspaper reporter, came for lunch.

entries.fullText:
went into N. J. to
11 Great Jones St - to see
about encyclopedia work
entries.summaryText: Went to 11 Great Jones St in N. J. to see about encyclopedia work.

entries.fullText: The boxes of old reports & papers for History - from Rochester came.
entries.summaryText: Received boxes of old reports and papers from Rochester for History.

entries.fullText: Had Scott carry all books & papers into the Tower of Mrs Stantons house - & there am to look them over & write & write
entries.summaryText: Moved books and papers to Mrs. Stanton's house to review and write.

entries.fullText: Tenafly - - Letter from Mrs E. R. Wentworth of Racine - Package of papers from Phila. came -- - Letter from sister Mary - [saying?] sister Hannah is to return to Kansas the First of August fear it is a mistake - still as I have written her - it is hard that in order to live at all - she must for ever live apart from all her loved ones - copied from old Revolution book - 1000 names & sent on to Ballot Box - & wrote a dozzen letters - rained all day - & I felt brisk for work -
entries.summaryText: Received letters and packages from Mrs. E. R. Wentworth, sister Mary, and copied 1000 names from an old Revolution book to send to Ballot Box.

entries.fullText: have written her - it is hard that in order to live at all - she must for ever live apart from all her loved ones - copied from old Revolution book - 1000 names & sent on to Ballot Box - & wrote a dozzen letters - rained all day - & I felt brisk for work -
Cool & delightful after 24 hours rain -
entries.summaryText: Cool and delightful weather after 24 hours of rain.

entries.fullText:
Phebe W. Couzens of
St. Louis came at
6 P.M. - on her
way home -
entries.summaryText: Phebe W. Couzens of St. Louis visited.

entries.fullText:
Lovely day. took a
ride with Miss Couzens
up the hill to Palisades
Hotel in A.M. - Letters from
sister to night from Denver - 21 & 25 July
Doctor says she must not come
east until cold weather - I fear
there is not cure for her
entries.summaryText: Went for a ride with Miss Couzens and received letters from sister.

entries.fullText:
Wrote Eugene, Sister Hannah
& Sister Mary - Phebe Couzins
left this A.M. - Guess she will
decide to marry - she has neither
the moral, mental nor physical
stamina to live in herself & her work
she looks outside for support
entries.summaryText: Wrote letters and Phebe Couzins left.
Hattie and Kitt rode over to Mr. Englands.

entries.fullText:
Hot day - did no
writing - Hattie & Kitt rode
over to Mr. Englands at
dusk
entries.summaryText: Hot day, did not write. Hattie and Kitt rode over to Mr. Englands.

entries.fullText:
Began looking over the
old papers & letters
to day - It is sad
work - & yet very interesting
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony is looking over old papers and letters.

entries.fullText:
Mrs. S & Self drove to Engle
Wood after dinner & called
on Dr. Geo. B. Cheever - he
is just the same grand
man - but sticks to his
narrow theology - he & wife
both seemed very glad of the call
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony and Mrs. S visit Dr. Geo. B. Cheever in Englewood.

entries.fullText:
Letter from brother Eugene
with letters from Frank & Sister
Hannah & one from sister Mary
with one from sister H. to me - dated
July 31st - stating she is breathing easier &
feeling full of hope & 'firm as a rock' -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony receives letters from family members.

entries.fullText:
To day have tried to
get ahead with Cyclopedia
notices - but my head is
heavy - constant pressure through
it from temple to temple that
is not actually pain - but next
door neighbor to it - Hattie talked
divorce with her mother -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony works on Cyclopedia notices and experiences head pressure. Hattie talks about divorce with her mother.

entries.fullText:
Wrote Mrs. A. J. Dunning - she
is at Council Bluffs -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes to Mrs. A. J. Dunning who is in Council Bluffs.
Susan B. Anthony did not write an entry on this day.

entries.fullText: Mrs. Paulina Wright Davis of Providence, R.I. died about 11.30 this A.M.- had been ill 3 yrs rheumatic gourt- terrible sufferer
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Paulina Wright Davis of Providence, R.I. died after a long illness.

entries.fullText: This evening's mail brought note from Kate Stanton--that Mr. Davis wished Mrs Stanton to be at P.W. Davis funeral--so she telegraphed Mr. P. that she & Susan would reach there Monday A. M.
entries.summaryText: Received a note from Kate Stanton about P.W. Davis funeral and made travel arrangements.

entries.fullText: Mrs. Stanton and self took train a 5.20 this P.M. for N.J. called an hour with Mrs. Phelps--then sleeping car for Providence
entries.summaryText: Traveled to N.J. with Mrs. Stanton and visited Mrs. Phelps before taking a sleeping car to Providence.

entries.fullText: --arrived Providence, at 5.10 A.M.--Theodore Tilton at Thomas Davis--Funeral at 2 P.M. Mrs. Stanton & self spoke--I read from Theo. Parkers diary--his feelings of loneliness for his unpopular beliefs--It was a sad funeral--Had not seen T.T. since the Dem. Con. of /72--at Baltimore--Mr. Davis handed my in P.M. D's note -
entries.summaryText: Attended Thomas Davis' funeral in Providence, spoke with Mrs. Stanton and read from Theo. Parkers diary.

entries.fullText: Spent forenoon looking over Mrs Davis' papers & letters--found but very little of any use to our history--marvelous how very little--Too 2 P.M. train & slept at Dr. Bayards-- only Sam'l Wilkerson there--Hadn't seen him since he testified on the Beecher Tilton - scandal--& he acted ashamed--as he ought to feel--
entries.summaryText: Reviewed Mrs. Davis' papers and letters, found very little of use. Traveled to Dr. Bayards and met with Sam'l Wilkerson.

entries.fullText: Spent A.M. in looking among publishers for our History--Mrs. S. at Mrs. E. B Phelps. Lunched with Mr Phelps-& came back to [T] to 1 P.M. train--found sundry letters--all well at home--
entries.summaryText: Looked for publishers for their history in the morning. Had lunch with Mr. Phelps and found letters upon returning home.

entries.fullText:
At Tenafly --Miss Helen
S. Potter came over & spent the
day--She personates me in her
entertainment this season. My answer
to Judge Hunt, why sentence should
not be pronounced.
entries.summaryText: Miss Helen S. Potter visits and impersonates Susan B. Anthony in her entertainment. Anthony writes about her answer to Judge Hunt.

entries.fullText:
Mrs. E.B. Phelps came over
& spent the day with Mrs. S
the England girls, came
just before lunch hour.
entries.summaryText: Mrs. E.B. Phelps visits and spends the day with Mrs. S and the England girls.

entries.fullText:
Kitt (Henry Jr.) staid at
home. all went to the
Palisades in the A.M.,
Andrew Paddock came-&
no letter from home or sister
Hannah- but one from dear
Mrs. Duniway- from Mount
Pulaska -Ill
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony goes to Palisades with others and receives a letter from Mrs. Duniway.

entries.fullText:
At Tenafly - N. Jersey
The England girls- Lizzie Paddock
& Julia E. here at Mrs. Stantons.
My heart is heavy as
if some great sorrow were
pressing down upon me
The prospect of getting a
history at all satisfactory seems
lessening.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about feeling heavy-hearted and the prospect of getting a satisfactory history lessening.

entries.fullText:
One of my
terrible head
colds cam on
& grows on me
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about having a terrible head cold.

entries.fullText:
Darning Stocking
for boys. With Mrs.
Stanton- all
history work broken
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony darns stockings with Mrs. Stanton and writes about broken history work.

entries.fullText:
Letter from Sister
Hannah of Aug 24th
- says she breathes easier
but cough is worse
& very hard & dry -
- & she can get nothing
satisfactory to eat - all
looks bad -
entries.summaryText: Susan receives a letter from her sister Hannah, who is not doing well.

entries.fullText:
The England
girls left this A.M -
So now we settle back
a little - cold better
to day - the first I have
come to tower write since
Sunday last - have felt
miserable enough - just seems
as if all of us have to follow dear
Gula - & not very long after
entries.summaryText: The England girls leave and Susan is feeling unwell.

entries.fullText:
SUNDAY 10
Maggie & Kitt drove
over to Mr Englands
to dinner - rained
at eveng when they
came home -
MONDAY 11
entries.summaryText: Maggie and Kitt have dinner at Mr. Englands and it rains when they return home.

entries.fullText: Among the papers
entries.summaryText: Working among papers

entries.fullText: Working among papers
entries.summaryText: Working among papers

entries.fullText: Working hard among old papers -
entries.summaryText: Working hard among old papers

entries.fullText:
Reception. W S. at Dr Loziers.
248 West 111th st - in honor of Mrs.
Margaret E. Parker of Dundee Scotland-
200 present- got fully 100
names to Declaration of Rights-
staid all night at Dr. Loziers-
Saturday 16
Spent the day at Dr. L's,
with Mrs. Parker- she
seems an earnest woman.
--at 5 she went to visit
Mrs. Soule- & at 5.45 I
returned to Tenafly- tired
enough - it began to rain down after
found Thomas Davis of Prov.
entries.summaryText: Attended a reception at Dr. Loziers in New York in honor of Mrs. Margaret E. Parker of Dundee Scotland. Got fully 100 names to Declaration of Rights. Spent the day with Mrs. Parker at Dr. L's. Found Thomas Davis of Prov.

entries.fullText:
Rained all last night
all this day- Thomas
Davis- husband of the late
Paulina W. Davis here at
Mrs Stantons to day-
This is Anniversary day of niece
Ann Eliza's death- 12 years ago
- wrote niece Maggie-
entries.summaryText: Thomas Davis, husband of the late Paulina W. Davis, was at Mrs. Stantons. This is the anniversary day of niece Ann Eliza's death 12 years ago. Wrote to niece Maggie.

entries.fullText: This is the 55th birthday of dear Sister Hannah--mothers 3rd born--who is now in Colorado fighting against the pall disease that swept our sister Gula off 3 yrs ago- Mrs Stanton drove Mr. Davis up to the Palisades this A.M.--
entries.summaryText: Celebrating Sister Hannah's birthday and mentioning Sister Gula's disease.

entries.fullText: Mrs. Margaret S. Parker of Dundee (The Cliff) Scotland-- came- she is pleasant & intelligent woman-- This is the 39th anniversary day of sister Gulema's marriage--and the 12th of the funeral day of her eldest born-Ann Eliza
