entries.summaryText: Mrs. Margaret S. Parker visits and mentions sister Gulema's anniversary and Ann Eliza's funeral day.

entries.fullText: I drove Mrs. Parker [?] to the Palisades--she tells us Mrs A.J. Dunniway arrived at Dr. Lozier's Sunday the 17th-- Judge Samuel L. Selden- died this eving--gave me shock that it was my noble & generous counsel Henry R. Selden
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Parker visits and mentions Mrs A.J. Dunniway's arrival and Judge Samuel L. Selden's death.

entries.fullText: Mrs. Parker left on 2.1 train P.M.--Mrs. L. & Hattie took ride to Palisades-- I gave Mrs. Parker a full set of National W.S. Con. reports- to take home, bind & keep for circulation-- also a sett of three Resolutions- sent Miss L.E. Becker a sett- a few weeks ago by express
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Parker leaves and Mrs. L. & Hattie take a ride to Palisades. Mrs. Parker is given a set of National W.S. Con. reports and Miss L.E. Becker is sent a set of three Resolutions.

entries.fullText: Mrs Stantons Hattie left for Vassar College- has two years more there- Maggie went with her- 9 P.M. no letter from sister Mary this even fear she is sick- I tremble lest she will break down with the load she has too carry- so heavy & so alone & so long- Then this attempt to write our history is simply appalling- it resigns us down to the bout of blue
entries.summaryText: Hattie and Maggie leave for Vassar College. No letter from sister Mary and mentions the difficulty of writing their history.

entries.fullText: Mrs Abigail Scott Dunniway- Portland, Oregon- came at night-
entries.summaryText: Abigail Scott Dunniway arrives from Portland, Oregon.

entries.fullText: SUNDAY, SEPTEMBER 24, 1876.

MONDAY 25
Mrs D. left at 3.45 - She wrote
sketch of herself in about 4 hours
entries.summaryText: Mrs D. left and wrote a sketch of herself.

entries.fullText: TUESDAY 26
WEDNESDAY, SEPTEMBER 27, 1876.
THURSDAY 28
FRIDAY 29
SATURDAY, SEPTEMBER 30, 1876
SUNDAY OCTOBER 1
MONDAY, OCTOBER 2

TUESDAY, OCTOBER 3, 1876
Mrs. Stantons sister Kate Wilkeson spent day with her- Brother Dan & sister Annie left Rochester for Phila. this eve.
entries.summaryText: Mrs. Stantons sister Kate Wilkeson spent day with her- Brother Dan & sister Annie left Rochester for Phila. this eve.

entries.fullText:
WEDNESDAY 4
Telegram from Sister Mary to go home. She ready to go to Philadelphia to Centennial - packed trunk - & copied Appeal to Women of the U.S. & worked to last minute & took 5.50 train for Jersey City - & Erie to Rochester -
entries.summaryText: Telegram from Sister Mary to go home. She ready to go to Philadelphia to Centennial - packed trunk - & copied Appeal to Women of the U.S. & worked to last minute & took 5.50 train for Jersey City - & Erie to Rochester -

entries.fullText:
THURSDAY 5
Arrived home at 11 A.M.- found all well- mother seeming quite as smart as a year ago - sister Mary not so thin as I feared -
entries.summaryText: Arrived home at 11 A.M.- found all well- mother seeming quite as smart as a year ago - sister Mary not so thin as I feared -

entries.fullText:
Lisler Mary took the 6. A.M.
Train Erie R. R. for Philadelphia
Wendall took satchel to Depot
With her began to rain at 7 A.M.
entries.summaryText: Lisler Mary left for Philadelphia on the Erie R.R. train.

entries.fullText:
Arthur Mosher and wife
Mattie, baby boy- Arthur- arrived this
A.M. from Centennial - trunk
left behind at Philadelphia
entries.summaryText: Arthur Mosher, his wife Mattie, and their baby boy Arthur arrived from Centennial, but their trunk was left behind in Philadelphia.

entries.fullText:
Arthur's trunk came
this A.M- and they
took the 10 P.M. train
for Leavenworth
entries.summaryText: Arthur's trunk arrived and they took the 10 P.M. train for Leavenworth.

entries.fullText:
Brother D.R. & Sister Annie
arrived from Centennial this A.M.
entries.summaryText: Brother D.R. & Sister Annie arrived from Centennial.

entries.fullText:
Aaron, Dan & Annie
went up to niece Maggie's
To dinner to day -
entries.summaryText: Aaron, Dan & Annie went up to niece Maggie's for dinner.

entries.fullText:
At Home- Brother
D.R. & Annie took 7.30 train
for Skaneateles - Went
to hear Geo. W. Curtis
lecture this evening - why he was
a republican -
entries.summaryText: Brother D.R. & Annie went to Skaneateles to hear Geo. W. Curtis lecture.

entries.fullText:
At Home - Brother D.R. &
Sister Annie bro't sad word from
Cousin Anson Lapham - has hemorage
of blood to the brain - not expected
to live & has known no one for two weeks
Brother Merritt arrived
from Centennial this A.M at
6 o'clock--
entries.summaryText: Brother D.R. & Sister Annie brought sad news about Cousin Anson Lapham. Brother Merritt arrived from Centennial.

entries.fullText:
at Rochester - Brother
D.R. & Annie left on 10 A.M.
train - Rev H.W. Beecher in
the Depot- on way to Congregational
con. at Lockport - could not catch
his eye, nor did I see him look at me
- Merritt & self drove to the farm - & he
carries home apples from the trees he & father
planted out -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony is in Rochester with her brother and Annie. They saw Rev H.W. Beecher at the depot. Merritt and Susan drove to the farm.

entries.fullText:
at Home -mother feeling
more poorly - like a chill -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony is at home with her mother who is feeling poorly.

entries.fullText:
Merritt & self went up
to Albion - at 1.15 - found
Lorinda gone from home - was
very uneasy about mother - but
she was much brighter when
we got back -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony and Merritt went to Albion. Lorinda was not home. Susan was worried about her mother but she was feeling better when they returned.

entries.fullText:
Brother Merritt took 10.25
train west - had the best
kind of a visit - left mother
in bed till I got back from
depot -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony's brother Merritt left after a good visit. Susan left her mother in bed while she went to the depot.

entries.fullText:
Cloudy - Sister Mary
returned home at 2 P.M.
via Erie R.R. - had a good
time -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony's sister Mary returned home via Erie R.R. and had a good time.

entries.fullText:
Went down town about
clothes - bonnet dresses hat
shoes - Telegram at 4 P.M. from
Joe Willetts - saying Cousin Anson
Lapham was gone & funeral Thursday--
- no man - save my own dear Father, ever
gave me such hearty trust & faith & his works
were equal to his faith
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony went shopping for clothes and received a telegram from Joe Willetts about Cousin Anson Lapham's funeral. She reflects on her father's trust and faith.

entries.fullText:
WEDNESDAY 25
The National Christian
women's temperance union
at Newark N.J. opens
this day -- Took 3 P.M.
train for Skaneatles - had to wait
at junction till 10 P.M. Then Jo. Lapham
& wife Edward & wife - Cynthia Peabody -
& others came from Syracuse - all staid?
at Hotel - save myself - found cousin
Thursday 26
Amy very feeble-- slept on lounge in
reception room - When Cousin Susan
always had his wood fire on the hearth
- The funeral at 3 P.M. - large
numbers of the cousins present - all
expectant of some revelations as to money
-- Sunderland Gardner was speaker
& ruugh & inappropriate it was too-
Cousin Amy & Willie & most of the cousins
left on 6.30 train with the remains- for
new york - buried in Brooklyn -
entries.summaryText: Attended the National Christian women's temperance union in Newark, took a train to Skaneatles, attended a funeral in Brooklyn.

people: Cousin Hannah Hathaway Mavis Keese Hill
entries.fullText:
Left Cousin Anson's house
& home at 10 A.M. with the last
of the visitors - Cousin Hannah
Hathaway Mavis Keese Hill & c -
& the Nichols sisters Mary & Maria -
- Did not stay at Auburn - how
hard it is to do since dear, noble
Martha C Wright is gone --
entries.summaryText: Left Cousin Anson's house and did not stay at Auburn, missing Martha C Wright.

entries.fullText:
At 5 P.M. niece Louise
& self took train for Buffalo
Cousin Geo O. Nail met us
at Depot & took us to his place
31 Irving Place - Mrs. Armstrong -
- had a warm welcome & good
visit- but Cousin G. is no
longer the charming intellect & [?]
of 20 years ago-
entries.summaryText: Took a train to Buffalo and visited Cousin Geo O. Nail and Mrs. Armstrong.

entries.fullText:
Temperence & Social [?] lecture
at Buffalo- W.H. Loomis
40 N. Main Street- had a good
audience- & the leading men
& women of the social expressed
much satisfaction-
entries.summaryText: Attended a Temperence & Social lecture in Buffalo by W.H. Loomis.

entries.fullText:
Left Buffalo on the 1.50 P.M.
train - Cousin Geo. drove us over
to East Buffalo depot - What a
shaddow his marriage blunder
throws over his whole life - it is
a cruel fate - vastly better no Marriage
at all - Found all well - mother
rested & stronger --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony leaves Buffalo and reflects on the consequences of marriage.

entries.fullText:
Called at Mary Hallowells
Antoinette Brown Blackwell told her
the reason she was afraid to work
publicly with S.B.A. that her theories
on Marriage were dangerous - that the
Beechers had a letter of S.B.'s that proved
it over her own name - Amy Post
called on me in P.M.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony discusses marriage theories with Antoinette Brown Blackwell and meets with Amy Post.

entries.fullText:
Took 4 P.M. Erie train
for Jersey City - It was harder
than ever to start out from home
after a stay of 4 weeks & one day
- called at Geo. L. Bakers store & for the
first time spoke to him of Maggies Pa
& the schoolmarm suit -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony travels to Jersey City and discusses Maggie's Pa and the schoolmarm suit with Geo. L. Bakers.

entries.fullText:
Arrived Tenafly at 10 A.M.
Found Mrs M.J. Gage & Mrs
Stanton on Piazza to greet me-
& Maggie ran to the gate
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrives in Tenafly and is greeted by Mrs M.J. Gage, Mrs Stanton, and Maggie.

entries.fullText:
At Mrs. Stanton's - Tenafly N.J.
Monday 6
Went into City to Cyclopedia-
Johnson's office - Mrs Stanton's
son Daniel Cady - (Neil) left
for Florida -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Mrs. Stanton in Tenafly, NJ and goes to the city to visit Johnson's office and the Cyclopedia. Daniel Cady and Neil were also present.

entries.fullText:
Election day - Hayes & Wheeler
Repub - Tilden & Hendricks Dem.
- Steady, soaking rain all day -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony notes that it is election day and that it is raining heavily.

entries.fullText:
First report came that Hayes
& Wheeler were elected -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony notes that the first report came in that Hayes and Wheeler were elected.

entries.fullText:
Went into N. J. City at 10
A.M. - Took six chapters history to
the Appletons - & proof of Cyclopedia
to Johnsons - Called on Mrs
Phelps & Mary L. Boothe - Mrs
Duniway's Literary reception at Dr
Loziers this evening- She read her poem -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony goes to N.J. City to visit the Appletons and Johnsons. She also visits Mrs. Phelps and Mary L. Boothe. In the evening, she attends Mrs. Duniway's Literary reception at Dr. Loziers where she reads her poem.

entries.fullText:
Called at Dr Mary Putnam Jacobi's
- she was out - it began to rain so
rushed back to Tenafly --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Dr. Mary Putnam Jacobi but she was out. She rushes back to Tenafly due to the rain.

entries.fullText:
Left Tenafly at 2.44 P.M.
to spend Sunday at Mr
A. P. Johnson's - then
Cyclopedia Publisher - lives
at 9 East 64th St - elegant
house - has wife & three children
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits Mr. A. P. Johnson's house in Tenafly.

entries.fullText:
Left Tenafly at 2.44 P.M.
to spend Sunday at Mr
A. P. Johnson's - then
Cyclopedia Publisher - lives
at 9 East 64th St - elegant
house - has wife & three children
entries.summaryText: No significant events mentioned.

entries.fullText:
at Mr Johnsons - rained
all day - went to hear
Rev. E. H. Chapin - Old time
generalistic sermon - Saw
Sinclair of the Old Tribune days
- it was here that Horace Greeley
used to worship or sleep on
Sunday mornings -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends a rainy day at Mr. Johnson's house and attends a sermon by Rev. E. H. Chapin. She also sees Sinclair, who used to work for the Old Tribune with Horace Greeley.

entries.fullText:
Rained all day long
so I did not start
out - Little hope of
help for woman as a
class from people suddenly
made rich -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony stays inside due to the rain and reflects on the lack of support for women from newly rich people.

entries.fullText:
Mrs Abigail Scott Duniway of Or.
& self attended the Lecture of
Victoria C. Woodhull, at [?]
Hall- this evening - paid $1. each -
- Mrs W. has verbally changed from
earnest simplicity, to affected stage
acting - ranting methodistic exhortation
no connected train of thought or
argument --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony and Mrs. Abigail Scott Duniway attend a lecture by Victoria C. Woodhull, but are disappointed by her performance.

entries.fullText:
Left Mrs Loziers at 10 A. M.
Mrs Duniway going to Colorado to work
till our Jan. Con. at Washington -
called on Cousin Eleanor & Geo. Caldwell
& reached Tenafly at 2 P.M. - found
letter from Sister Mary - she does have a
hard try with the two brothers in law -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony leaves Mrs. Loziers and visits relatives before returning to Tenafly. She receives a letter from her sister Mary, who is having trouble with her brothers-in-law.

entries.fullText:
At Tenafly
trying to concentrate
on speech for
Boston
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony is at Tenafly trying to concentrate on a speech for Boston.

entries.fullText:
At Tenafly
Waking up tomorrow
beginning to write--
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony is at Tenafly and plans to begin writing tomorrow.

entries.fullText:
Susan A King and Madam Demorest
visited Mrs Stanton's this day- to
talk over establishing a stock
Co. to found a newspaper- Madam
Demorest presented me with $10--
This is the 14th anniversary observance
of the death of our dear
dear father- this date
always brings him to me--
entries.summaryText: Susan A King and Madam Demorest visit Mrs Stanton's to talk about establishing a stock company to found a newspaper. Madam Demorest presented Susan B. Anthony with $10. It is also the 14th anniversary of the death of Susan's father.

entries.fullText:
Snowed & rained--
Kitt came at 10 A.M.--&
Maggie & he returned to City
at 5.30 P.M.--Can't
get under way yet--
Would the good spirits--
or my own brain would
come to the rescue--
entries.summaryText: It snowed and rained. Kitt and Maggie visited and left. Susan B. Anthony is having trouble getting started and wishes for inspiration.

entries.fullText:
Left Tenafluy at 10 A.M.
& took 2 P.M. train at New York
for Bridgeport-- Lectured
there--found Olympia with
a 3 week old baby--
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Tenafluy and gave a lecture in Bridgeport where she met Olympia with a 3 week old baby.

entries.fullText:
Left Olympia at 10 A.M.
and reached Boston at 5--
went to Tremont Hotel--
Mr. [Mendum?] called in
evening
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony left Olympia and arrived in Boston where she stayed at Tremont Hotel and was visited by Mr. [Mendum?].

entries.fullText:
Left Olympia at 10 A.M.
and reached Boston at 5--
went to Tremont Hotel--
Mr. [Mendum?] called in
evening
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony arrived in Boston and stayed at Tremont Hotel where she was visited by Mr. [Mendum?].

entries.fullText:
--William Lloyd Garrison Jr.
called at Tremont house--for me
to go & hear Wendell Phillips--but
I did not dare to take the time
from my evening speech--Had fair
audience at Paine Hall--
Horace Seaner introduced me
entries.summaryText: William Lloyd Garrison Jr. visited Susan B. Anthony at Tremont house and invited her to hear Wendell Phillips, but she couldn't attend due to her evening speech. She had a fair audience at Paine Hall and was introduced by Horace Seaner.

entries.fullText:
My room at Tremont was
directly opposite the women's journal
office--Lucy & all knew I was
there--but none of them called
--Miss Hindman, Rucker & Malloy
called--at 5 I went over
to Melrose with Mr. [Wondu?]
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony stayed at Tremont and none of the women from the journal office visited her. Miss Hindman, Rucker, and Malloy called. She went to Melrose with Mr. [Wondu?] at 5.

entries.fullText:
Miss Mendum walked with
me to Samuel Lewalls - their
house seemed closed - then we
walked round to Mrs. [Linemere's?] -
she was not in -- her poor Lizzie was -
- Went into Boston at 3. P.M., and
out to Chelsea - to Mrs. Annie C. Cheney
found letter from Mrs Hooker
entries.summaryText: Miss Mendum walked with me to Samuel Lewalls and then to Mrs. [Linemere's?]. Went into Boston and out to Chelsea to Mrs. Annie C. Cheney. Found letter from Mrs Hooker.

entries.fullText:
The Woman Suffrage Club of
Chelsea - met at Parlors of Mrs
Strickland - Mrs Cheney & Mrs Osgood
asked Lucy Stone if it would be agreeable
to have Miss Anthony invited to be present
- Lucy said no - So I was left at
Ms. Osgoods till 5 P.M. when they returned
Miss Ricker with them - that showed the
[animosity?] of [my?] [?]
entries.summaryText: The Woman Suffrage Club of Chelsea met. Lucy Stone said no to Miss Anthony being invited to be present. Miss Ricker was with them later.

entries.fullText:
Chelsea - gave 16th amendment
in Hawthorn Hall - for admission
a good audience - but quite a number
went out after listening 20 or 30 minutes -
never had so many leave a house
before - it was a closely written
argument
entries.summaryText: Gave 16th amendment in Hawthorn Hall in Chelsea. Good audience but quite a number left after listening 20 or 30 minutes.

entries.fullText:
At Mrs. Cheney's - day
pleasant - -
entries.summaryText: At Mrs. Cheney's. Day pleasant.

entries.fullText:
Terrible wind storm -
all the day & the night -
still more terrific --
entries.summaryText: Terrible wind storm all day and night.

entries.fullText:
Paine Hall -Bread & Ballot
Mrs. Ricker came over to Cheneys
to dinner & went with me to
Paine Hall - dreadfully
cold & windy - Small audience,
I went home with Wm & Ellen
Wright Garrison-
entries.summaryText: Paine Hall - Bread & Ballot. Mrs. Ricker came over to Cheneys to dinner and went with me to Paine Hall. Dreadfully cold and windy. Small audience. I went home with Wm & Ellen Wright Garrison.

entries.fullText:
Salem - Mrs. Mary G. Ward
called at Mr. Garrisons in A.M.
Sarah Southwick there - long talk on
Repub. Party- & Woman Suffrage -
- Small audience at Salem - my
old associate - Daniel B. Hagar of
Canajoharie present - & gave me highest
compliment for my argument
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony meets with Mary G. Ward and Daniel B. Hagar in Salem to discuss the Republican Party and Woman Suffrage.

entries.fullText:
Mrs. Ward took me to Prof.
Hagar's school - State Normal -
200 girls - then to call on Mrs. H
& then to call on Richie
Remond - Charles & wife dead -
Mrs. Putnam - & Sarah P. in
Florence Italy - only Richie &
Susan at Salem - the P.M. went
to Peabody - to Womens Temp. meeting.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visits State Normal and meets with various people in Salem.

entries.fullText:
Returned to Boston - slush
& snow - called at 7 Groten St - on
Lydia Maria Child - then to
Mrs. Rickers - 27 Motte St. - & then
to Ellen Wright Garrison's - found Mrs.
Phelps daughter there - very afraid I
would publish something of her mothers
insanity in our history
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony returns to Boston and visits various people.

entries.fullText:
Took the 11 A.M. train for
Hartford - found Mrs. Hooker
glad to see me - first meeting
since the B. & T. scandal - both
Mrs & Mr Hooker thoroughly believe
Mr B. guilty of the first charge & of perjury
& that the burden of guilt will eventually
be too great - & that he will confess.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony meets with Mrs. Hooker in Hartford and discusses Mr. B's guilt.

entries.fullText:
At Hartford - Mrs H. read
me her Spiritual experiences
& illuminations - thinks herself a
medium - said Martha C.
Wright tried to get control of her
to talk to me - but could not entirely.
- Spirits reveal to her that she is to be
President in 1880 - & S.B.A. to be her
Sec'y of the Interior - !! - the only woman
in her cabinet -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony meets with Mrs. H and Ellen F. Burr in Hartford and discusses spiritual experiences and future plans.

entries.fullText:
Spent Friday night
at the Burrs - Ellen F. Burr
believes she hears rapps - & feels
great comfort in spirit presences
-- She took me to Depot
at 10 A.M. - reached Florence
at 2 P.M. Stopped with dear
Elizabeth Powell Bond--
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony spends time with Ellen F. Burr and travels to Florence to stay with Elizabeth Powell Bond.

entries.fullText: Florence Mass - before their [Free?] Church - A. G. Hill - the Sec'y - son of L. S. Hill - the silk manufacturer - Mr. Lillie - head man - Mr. Hammond - Henry H. Bond - Dr. Leonard & wife - Had good audience - though fearfully cold
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had a good audience in Florence Mass despite the cold weather.

entries.fullText: Terrific snow storm - Dr. Leonard took me to street car at 10 [?] snow turned to rain & it poured from Hartford to N. J. arrived at 5 - called on Mrs M. J. Gage- 314 E. 9th St - & then at 9 oclock to Dr. Loziers--
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony traveled during a snow storm to visit Mrs. M. J. Gage and Dr. Loziers.

entries.fullText: Went to Appleton's - couldn't decide about History publishing - then to Johnsons - read proof of W. R. article - very good - long call & lunch with Mrs. Phelps - then to Susan A. Kings - to talk up Stock Co. to review Revolution She seems in real earnest
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony had a long day visiting Appleton's, Johnsons, Mrs. Phelps, and Susan A. Kings.

entries.fullText: Went to Appleton's again - Want to wait decision till after New Years - thence to Laura Curtis Bullard's - staid to Lunch - Mr & Mrs Curtis gave me a cordial greeting - T.T. had just left - ran in from train to breakfast & then off for Albany - returned to Tenafly- at 4 P.M. -- found Bob & Theodore home for holidays--
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visited Appleton's and Laura Curtis Bullard's before returning to Tenafly to find Bob and Theodore home for the holidays.

entries.fullText: My New York Life Policy annual premium due this day - Policy No. 10733- amount $61 - paid $37 & some cents Snow storm - glad I am in harbor - found letter from Sister Mary - Brother Aaron still pursuing his butterfly - oh, how nothing it will be to him after he has over clasped it.
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony paid her New York Life Policy annual premium and received a letter from Sister Mary about Brother Aaron.

entries.fullText: My left eye tooth sore - & ulcerated at root - & Dentist tells me it is a dead tooth - -had it bored to the place of old nerve - & it was dead as a door nail - it gives me a shock to learn it --
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony visited the dentist and learned that her left eye tooth was dead.

entries.fullText:
& Kitt home today - & a
splendid roast turkey dinner
-with best heart & soul of the
dear faithful Amelia Willard
[fast?] into the work - x but no
husband & father out to enjoy
it with them - & no seeming care that
their is not x
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about having a splendid roast turkey dinner with Hattie, Maggie, Bob, Theodore, and Amelia Willard.

entries.fullText:
Received letter & report of Manchester Eg.
W. S. doing annual meeting - from Lydia
E Decker - - Another lonely day
& splendid turkey dinner -
plum-pudding & all -
Wrote letter to Miss King
about Revolution Corporation
I do hope she will give us the
lift needed - financially -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about receiving a letter and report from Lydia E Decker about Manchester Eg. W. S. doing annual meeting and having a splendid turkey dinner. She also wrote a letter to Miss King about Revolution Corporation.

entries.fullText:
Just 22 years ago - at
2 Oclock this P.M. - I began my
great canvass of 54 County Con
ventions
of State of New York -
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about the 22nd anniversary of her great canvass of 54 County Conventions of State of New York.

entries.fullText:
Brother Eugene Mosher left
Rochester, this P.M. for Leavenworth
Kan - Sister Hannah & Frank
gone to keeping house in Arthurs
house - till Spring - Sen. Marshall
sick - & Brother D.R. gives Eugene
his place in P. Office - It looks like
a big job for Sister Hannah, but
she must try her own experiments--
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about Brother Eugene Mosher leaving Rochester for Leavenworth, Kansas, and Sister Hannah and Frank going to keep house in Arthur's house until Spring. She also mentions Sen. Marshall being sick and Brother D.R. giving Eugene his place in P. Office.

entries.fullText:
Mrs England, Father Dillings
here to dinner - failed to go to
Dentist at Englewood - Letter from
Sister Mary - telling that Mother & she
took Christmas dinner at Huldah
Anthony's - with all of her children
their wives & grand children -
& that mother did not get cold
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about having Mrs England and Father Dillings over for dinner and receiving a letter from Sister Mary telling her about Mother and her taking Christmas dinner at Huldah Anthony's with all of her children, their wives, and grand children, and that Mother did not get cold.

entries.fullText: Tenafly - a severe snow storm
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about a severe snow storm in Tenafly.

entries.fullText: SATURDAY 30
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about Saturday 30th, but does not provide any additional information.

entries.fullText: Brother Aaron McLean rounds out his 64th year to day- his 2 score years & four- 6 more to make his allotted- and yet he is flirting with a school marm 30 years his junior-
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about her brother Aaron McLean's 64th birthday and his flirtation with a younger woman.

entries.fullText: Mrs S and I wrote 20 letters to prominent men to get letters to Wash. Con.-
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes about writing letters to prominent men to get letters to Washington Convention.

entries.fullText: Memoranda want lectures
entries.summaryText: Susan B. Anthony writes a memorandum about wanting lectures.

people: I. L. Funk; W. H. Timerlake; A. E. Gregory; J. A. Shipley; Thomas Carlin; John R. Colton; A. P. Morehouse; J F Sehorn; P. V. Wise; Mrs. Geo. Hollowell; Geo. T. Young; Ms Orville Croxen; J. O. Daniels; Mrs Susie P Cheney; M. D. Skeels; Alfred B. Mason
entries.fullText:
I. L. Funk- Chillicothe- MO 450
W. H. Timerlake- Columbus- MO
A. E. Gregory- Carthage- MO
J. A. Shipley- Springfield- MO
Thomas Carlin- Pierce City- MO
John R. Colton- Denver- Col
A. P. Morehouse- Marysville- MO $50
J F Sehorn- Ed. Dem.- Marengo-In
P. V. Wise- St Joseph- MO
Mrs. Geo. Hollowell- Winona- Minn
Geo. T. Young- Mt. Ayr- Iowa
Ms Orville Croxen- Attalissa- Iowa
J. O. Daniels- Lathrop- Mo
Mrs Susie P Cheney- 61 Hawthorne St- Chelsea, M??
M. D. Skeels- Quitman Mo
